<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (21): Safe hands are needed to pass
it on - Trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CAROLINE GARNHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF ALICE gives Bob money to invest for Claire in such a way that Bob,
thereafter, owns that money, not for himself, but for Claire the legal
relationship between Alice, Bob and Claire is that of a trust. Alice is the
settlor, Bob the trustee and Claire the beneficiary.
A change of ownership from Alice to Bob is essential to create a trust. This
is what makes a trust different from any other legal arrangement, and also
the reason why, unless specified to the contrary, the settlor has no further
rights over or entitlement to the trust assets after the trust has been
created.
This does not mean that the trustees can do with the trust assets what they
choose. If a trustee in any way benefits from the trust assets, unless
specified by the settlor at the time of creating the trust, or deals
recklessly with the trust assets, he can be sued by the beneficiary.
The settlor's instructions to his or her trustees are usually contained in a
Trust Deed, which should be carefully drafted by a lawyer, so as to reflect
the settlor's wishes accurately.
The unique legal relationship of a trust is of great importance in commerce.
Trusts are widely used, for example, in pension schemes, share employment
schemes, investment transactions and joint ventures.
Trusts have also traditionally been used to provide for the weak and needy,
and for those beneficiaries such as widows, charities, infant children and
future generations, so that capital is protected and preserved in the safe
hands of the trustees (one of whom could also be the settlor).
Not surprisingly, the unique legal relationship of the trust means that it
must be taxed differently, from either an individual or a company. Trustees
cannot be taxed on trust income and trust capital as if it were their own
personal income or capital to enjoy; neither can the funds simply be added
to the beneficiary's income or personal capital, because a beneficiary has
no control over these funds and in many cases does not receive any money
until much later, if at all.
Trusts are taxed according to the type of trust and the relationship between
the settlor and the beneficiary. They are categorised, depending on what the
trustees do with the income of the trust fund. If the trustees must pay all
the income of the trust to a particular beneficiary - the 'life tenant' -
the trust is an 'Interest in Possession' trust. All other trusts are
'Discretionary' trusts, because the trustees either have discretion as to
which beneficiary should receive the income or how much the beneficiary
should get, leaving the trustees free to accumulate what remains of the
income with the existing capital of the trust fund.
One important sub-class of the Discretionary trust is the 'Accumulation and
Maintenance' trust for children under the age of 25. Provided the conditions
set out in inheritance tax legislation are met, the penal inheritance tax
provisions imposed on Discretionary trusts can then be avoided.
Because trusts are taxed in a different, often more advantageous way, from
either individuals or companies, they are often used as part of a family tax
mitigation scheme. The table sets out the tax effects of the various
settlements.
The most tax-effective trust is one set up by a 'Non-UK domiciled' settlor
for a UK resident beneficiary with trustees resident in a tax haven. This
trust can effectively avoid UK income tax, capital gains tax and inheritance
tax if carefully structured and managed.
If a trust is to be used as part of a tax mitigation exercise, it must be
remembered that a trust cannot always be changed at a later date, if the tax
regime changes or the settlor decides that he or she needs the money
personally. A trust should therefore be treated with respect and should not
be entered into lightly.
Caroline Garnham is a tax and trusts lawyer for the City firm of Simmons &amp;
Simmons.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                Trust for children under the age of 18*
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                  Income tax     Capital gains tax    Inheritance tax
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Interest in       Income taxed   Capital gains        No IHT
possession        at settlor's   taxed at 25%         provided
                  rate                                settlor
Accumulation      Accumulated    Capital gains        survives
and maintenance   income         taxed at 35%         seven years
                  taxed at 35%
Discretionary     Distributed                         IHT paid at 20%
                  income                              max on creation
                  taxed at                            intervivos or
                  settlor's                           40% on death,
                  rate                                and at 6% max
                                                      every 10 years
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
*UK trust with UK-domiciled parent settlor, for the benefit of
settlor's children
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Simmons &amp; Simmons
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
              Trust for children or grandchildren over 18*
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                  Income tax     Capital gains tax    Inheritance tax
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Interest in       Income taxed   taxed at 25%         No IHT
possession        at beneficiary's                    provided
                  rate                                settlor
                                                      survives
Accumulation      Accumulated    Capital gains        seven years
and maintenance   income         taxed at 35%
                  taxed at 35%
Discretionary     Distributed                         IHT paid at 20%
                  income                              on intervivos
                  taxed at                            or 40% on
                  beneficiary's                       death, and
                  rate                                6% max every
                                                      10 years
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
*UK trust with UK-domiciled grandparent settlor or UK-domiciled parent
settlor, for benefit of settlor's grandchildren or settlor's children
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Simmons &amp; Simmons
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
