<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (20): Choose the place, then the
route - School fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT EDUCATION has a reputation for being elitist. High fees, which
are increasing ahead of the rate of inflation, could make this even worse.
Meanwhile, falling interest rates have forced parents to take a slightly
higher level of risk if they want to plan ahead.
But forward-planning can still bring independent education within the range
of many families who feel that will give their children an advantage.
School fees can become an even bigger financial commitment than a house
purchase, which justifies making a special, ear-marked plan. But financial
considerations should not be allowed to dictate the choice of school - one
of the most important decisions a family ever makes. If you want to send
your child to a big city single-sex day school - and FT surveys continually
suggest that these provide the best value for money - you will have less of
a problem meeting fees than you would with a famous boarding school.
Once you have chosen a school, or produced a short list, contact bursars to
find out what the current fees are and for an estimate of what they could be
in future. Remember that you are aiming for a fixed commitment at a set
time, and that securing more than the fees would be There is no point in
saving more than you need.
While you will probably need a disciplined plan to reach the target, it does
not follow either that financial providers should impose extra discipline on
you through punitive and inflexible charges, or that all your money should
be put into one investment. Pre-packaged 'school fees plans' do not
necessarily offer decent value for money.
Your tax position is also of crucial importance in deciding which schemes
make most sense - for example, if one partner is a non-taxpayer, they should
use up their income tax allowance in a deposit account before trying
anything more technical.
Once these principles are in place, there are three routes to paying school
fees, which will depend on your capital resources, and on the length of time
before your child starts at school:
From capital. Those able to pay fees with a lump sum have a broad range of
opportunities.
The classic solution is the educational trust. Funds in an educational trust
can be invested tax-free, provided they are used to pay school fees - no
specific school or pupil need be named. Life offices offer these trusts,
accepting a fixed lump sum and then guaranteeing a certain level of fees
through a series of annuities commencing at a certain point. But this can be
expensive, as the guarantees are costly to fund - particularly now that gilt
yields have come down.
Thus advisers suggest they should only be used for part of fees, and should
be restricted to 40 per cent taxpayers who have used up both their personal
income tax allowances and their annual CGT allowance.
Products ahead of them in the queue include personal equity plans, Tessas
(tax-exempt special savings accounts) and zero-dividend shares of investment
trusts, which offer a fixed return taxed as capital gains (useful for those
who do not pay capital gains tax).
Those certain of the school their child will attend might ask about
'composition schemes' where you pay a lump sum in advance, at a level which
usually saves you money compared with paying fees as they arise. Such
schemes are not transferable, which is the big disadvantage.
From income. This is the way most people have to do it, and the traditional
recommended method is the with-profits endowment. But the 'sum assured' will
never be enough to pay school fees on its own.
Other vehicles include Pep savings schemes, which are more flexible and
tax-efficient, and a range of cash-based schemes, such as Tessas and
National Savings. Of the latter, Children's Bonus Bonds have been designed
specifically for saving on behalf of children.
You could also buy a friendly society bond on behalf of your child - this is
inflexible, but savings of Pounds 18 per month can be kept in a totally
tax-free environment for the child, provided you keep paying in the money
for 10 years.
Equity-based products make more sense if there is still a long time to go
before the child starts school. Cash-backed investments should take a larger
share of the portfolio if the first day at school is nearer.
From a Loan. This is only to be recommended if the start of the child's
independent education is imminent, and there is no other way of paying for
it.
Probably the best loan scheme available is offered by Isis (the Independent
Schools' Information Service) in conjunction with advisers Claremont Savile
and the Halifax building society. This allows you to draw down the loan as
and when you need it to pay fees, so you do not need to take all the debt up
front as with a mortgage. Halifax has made no stipulations about how you
repay the loan, so you can save towards it using any investment vehicle you
like.
</TEXT>
