<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (19): You'll need to top up NI
benefits - Retirement Planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS FACE a bewildering array of different pension products, and before
entering the maze it is worth going back to basics to familiarise yourself
with the three main sources: occupational schemes, private individual plans
and the state.
Most people end up with a combination of at least two, and usually all
three, elements, so it is important that you and your pensions adviser take
each into consideration before planning ahead.
The state scheme provides the 'old age' flat-rate pension and an
earnings-related pension, both of which are based on an individual's
National Insurance contribution record. NI is paid at 9 per cent by most
employees. For the 1993-94 tax year, the lower and upper thresholds are
Pounds 56 and Pounds 420 a week.
The old-age pension is a maximum of Pounds 56.10 a week for the 1993-94 tax
year, while the earnings-related pension (Serps) will be a maximum of
between 20 and 25 per cent of middle-band earnings, depending on your NI
record and when you retire. Middle-band earnings are those earnings that
fall between the lower and upper NI thresholds. Employees who are not in a
'contracted out' company scheme or personal pension plan will automatically
be in Serps.
Clearly, even with a full NI record, the combination of state pensions is
not going to keep you in clover. For this reason most people make extra
provision, either through a company pension or through personal pensions and
other similar plans.
Company schemes and private individual plans approved by the Inland Revenue
are extremely tax-efficient. Contributions are paid free of basic and
higher-rate tax, the pension fund builds up tax-free, and a significant
chunk of the accumulated fund can be taken as tax-free cash at retirement.
The pension itself is taxed as income.
A good company pension scheme will also provide widow's and dependants'
pensions, death-in-service benefits of up to four times the member's salary,
long-term disability pensions and, increasingly, membership of the group
private medical scheme.
Occupational schemes in the UK cover about 50 per cent of employees,
representing over 11m people. Massive funds, in total estimated at Pounds
300bn, support these arrangements which are set up predominantly on a
final-salary basis, although a growing number of schemes are moving to
money-purchase.
Under a final-salary, or 'defined benefit' scheme, the pension is linked to
the value of the employee's salary at retirement. Employees usually
contribute 5 to 6 per cent of salary, while most employers at least match
this rate and often pay considerably more for older members.
Typically, the pension builds up at the rate of 1/60th of final salary for
each year of service, up to a Revenue maximum of 40/60ths, or two-thirds of
final salary after 40 years' service. Where tax-free cash is taken, the
pension is reduced. (Public sector schemes tend to build up on an '80ths'
basis, but add the tax-free cash on top of the pension, which makes them
roughly equivalent to the '60ths' schemes.)
Certain high earners will find their contributions and final pension
restricted by the 'earnings cap'. The cap, which represents the maximum
salary that can be taken into consideration for pension purposes, was
introduced in the 1989 Budget, and is worth Pounds 77,400 for the 1993-94
tax year. It applies to members of final-salary schemes set up after the
1989 Budget and members who joined any final-salary schemes after June 1,
1989. However, there are less tax-efficient 'unapproved' Revenue schemes
available, which help build up pensions for earnings above the cap.
Few employees achieve a full two-thirds pension at retirement, particularly
if they have changed jobs several times. Fortunately, it is possible to top
up a company pension by paying into an additional voluntary contribution
(AVC) scheme, usually run by a life office on behalf of the employer. AVCs
are individual money-purchase plans that can be used to provide extra
pension either through the purchase of an annuity or, in some cases, by
boosting the company pension itself. Free-standing AVCs (FSAVCs) are also
available, mainly from the life offices. The maximum total contribution to
the company scheme and (FS)AVC combined is 15 per cent of earnings.
Group money-purchase, or 'defined contribution' schemes do not link the
pension to the final salary. Instead, contributions are invested to provide
a fund at retirement, which is used to purchase an annuity to provide an
income for life. The value of the fund - and hence the annuity - is not
guaranteed but will depend on the provider's investment performance, policy
charges and the prevailing annuity rates at the time of purchase.
There are two basic options under this type of group scheme - contracted-out
money-purchase schemes (comps) and, by far the most popular with employers,
group personal pensions. Comps are also available on a contracted-in basis,
where the pension provided by the scheme sits on top of the Serps pension
rather than replacing it.
There are a few differences between comps and group personal pensions, but
the pros and cons of each tend to be outweighed by more important factors,
such as the employer's rate of contribution (sometimes nil, but generally
about 3 per cent) and the investment performance of the chosen fund.
Most group schemes - whether final-salary or money-purchase - are contracted
out of Serps and receive a rebate of NI contributions. In return,
final-salary schemes promise to provide a guaranteed minimum pension (gmp)
to replace the Serps benefit foregone. Very few money-purchase schemes offer
this guarantee.
The self-employed and employees who do not have access to a suitable group
scheme can take out a personal pension. These were introduced in 1987 and
replaced the old-style self-employed retirement annuity. Although it is
still possible to contribute to an existing retirement annuity, new
contracts are not available.
'Appropriate' personal pensions allow employees to contract out of Serps and
claim the NI rebate. This is calculated as a percentage of middle-band
earnings. Almost 5m employees have taken out personal pensions and will be
eligible for the rebate, which is worth up to Pounds 1,500 for the 1992-93
tax year for those earning over Pounds 21,000. The rebate is sent direct to
your chosen provider, who invests it in the fund of your choice.
However, a rebate-only plan will not provide a decent pension on its own, so
you should also try to pay an extra contribution to top up the rebate plan.
Like all money-purchase arrangements, on retirement the accumulated fund is
used to provide an element of tax-free cash, and the remainder is used to
purchase an annuity.
Personal pensions are available from a range of financial institutions, but
the market is dominated by the life offices. A handful of unit trust groups
and friendly societies also run their own scheme, but most banks and
building societies act as tied agents and offer the pension products of a
life office.
Finally, it is important to appreciate that investments in a pension scheme
or AVC are locked away until retirement, and even with personal pensions you
cannot take the benefits until at least age 50. For this reason, in some
circumstances pensions advisers also recommend the use of other
tax-efficient savings vehicles such as personal equity plans (Peps) and
tax-exempt special savings accounts (Tessas) which tie up your money for
much shorter periods.
 ------------------------------------------
   PERSONAL PENSION: CONTRIBUTION LIMITS
 ------------------------------------------
Age                      % Earnings
Up to 35                 17.5
36-45                    20
46-50                    25
51-55                    30
56-60                    35
61-74                    40
 ------------------------------------------
