<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (18): How to give advisers the
litmus test - Questions you should ask
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN EDWARDS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL ADVISERS come in many different guises. They can be an alternative
name for insurance company or unit trust salesmen; employees of banks or
building societies; or pukka financial consultants.
So the first question when dealing with financial advisers should be aimed
at checking that they are authorised to give investment advice, and on what
subjects.
That sorts out the wheat from the chaff. If you receive an honest answer,
you should at least know whether you are talking to an independent financial
adviser, company representative or a 'tied' agent.
The company representatives and tied agent should explain that they are only
able to offer the range of products sold by one particular company.
But salesmen are salesmen. Therefore you might need to ask a few
supplementary questions to get a really clear picture. Ask to see a
letterhead and/or business card. Asking for the name of the adviser's boss
or contact at the company gives you someone to complain to if something goes
wrong, and a possible checkpoint if you feel you are being misled.
Once you have established what type of adviser you are dealing with, the
next stage is to assess their status and competence. With company
representatives and tied agents, this is mainly a check on the company they
are representing. Has it got a good name and a reputation to protect, or
have you never heard of it?
It is a bit more difficult with independent advisers. You can ask how long
they have been in business, how many people are employed, and what
qualifications or experience the adviser has. Also, what they are authorised
to advise upon; and whether they are specialists in any particular areas.
In both cases you can then check with the central register of all the
authorised firms of investment advisers, maintained by the Securities and
Investments Board (SIB). The register lists their names, addresses and a
description of the sort of business they are allowed to undertake.
It also states whether or not the firm is permitted to handle clients' money
 -another important question.
If their names are not on the central register, prepare to move away smartly
with your hand on your wallet.
Competence and honesty, are more difficult to assess. However, you might
prepare a few trick questions where you know the answers, and see whether
the adviser looks blank, bluffs or gives correct replies. The simplest
questions are often the most revealing.
For example, two questions that might reveal whether the adviser is only
interested in commission-earning products are: What's the difference between
an investment trust and a unit trust? What are the current rates being paid
on National Savings products?
Another safeguard is to ask advisers to put their recommendations down in
writing, so that you can judge them in the cold light of day.
Possibly the most crucial question is how the adviser is remunerated -
salary, bonuses, commission or fees. Unfortunately, with company
representatives you are unlikely to get a straight answer. They are not
obliged to tell you how and what they are paid. Tied agents are also not
bound to reveal their commission and charging arrangements.
Independent financial advisers, however, must give you details of how much
they will earn from providing you with a particular product, provided you
ask specifically.
Most independent advisers still rely on commission for the bulk of their
earnings, and this can obviously influence their judgment.
However, equally relevant is how the individual consultant is remunerated.
Some independent advisers pay their consultants salaries only to prevent
their being swayed by the need to earn commission. Others pay a mixture of
salary and commission to their consultants or themselves.
Alternatively, there are a growing number of fee-based advisers who charge
'up front' for their services, although most of them do not rely exclusively
on fees.
The few simple questions listed with this article should at least prevent
your being led up the garden path. Whether the advice proves to be any good
is another matter.
Key questions to ask a financial adviser:
Are you authorised to give investment advice, and if so by whom?
Are you fully independent, or are you employed or tied to a particular
company and only able to recommend its products?
Are you authorised to handle clients' money?
What types of business are you authorised to give advice on, and are you
permitted to operate discretionary accounts?
Are you prepared to put your advice in writing?
How are you remunerated? Salary only; salary plus bonuses and/or commission;
commission only; fees only, or a mixture of fees and commission.
John Edwards is a consultant with Berry Birch &amp; Noble
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
