<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (17): Liquidity, security and equity
 -Portfolio planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS normally acquire investments on a haphazard basis: a word from a
friend here; a newspaper article there; the persuasion of a salesman
somewhere else.
But how does one work out a sensible portfolio of investments and policies
which actually meet your needs? There is no magic formula that applies to
everyone, which is why advisers and salesmen have to take you through a
fact-find when they first meet you.
John Cole, of financial advisers Berry, Birch &amp; Noble, says that investors
should sit down with a blank piece of paper and write down all their sources
of income and their normal expenditure, and see what money is surplus and
thus available for investment.
Then they should think about their ultimate objective, whether it is
providing for school fees, retirement or a daughter's wedding. Most people
have an inflated idea of what their pension will actually be worth; just
finding out what your pension benefits are is a useful exercise in itself.
Make sure you have the basics in place. If you have dependants, do you have
life insurance? You may find this is provided by your work; if not, then
term assurance is the cheapest way of providing what you need. There is no
investment element to term assurance; it is just like house or car
insurance. If you do not make a claim, you do not get any premiums back.
Savers should also decide what level of risk they are happy with. Mr Cole
says it is vital that the investor understands the product he or she is
buying and is comfortable with it.
Once you have a clear idea of your current financial position, your
financial goals, and your attitude to risk, then you can start to think
about your portfolio.
Mr Cole says any portfolio should have three elements: liquidity, a backbone
of guarantee and security, and equity-related growth products.
Broadly speaking, the younger you are, or the longer term your goals, the
greater the proportion of your portfolio that should be in shares. This is
because, over the long term, equities have provided the best returns.
But shares can, of course, be risky in the short term. So anyone saving for
the next holiday, or an elderly person who needs income, should limit the
equity proportion.
The best way for the small investor to get into shares is via a unit or
investment trust. These buy a widespread portfolio of stocks, and thus
reduce the risk of one company going wrong. If held in a personal equity
plan, all income and gains are tax-free. Again, the advantages of a Pep show
through in the long term; in the short term, the charges can easily destroy
the tax benefits, especially for a basic-rate taxpayer.
Buying an indexed fund which grows in line with the FT-SE 100 or the
All-Share wipes out the risk of picking a poor-performing fund manager. The
charges are lower, too.
For the cautious, guaranteed equity products provide a way to get some of
the benefits of share investment without risking your original capital.
Turning to the 'secure' portion of the portfolio, investors could consider
the following:
National Savings. Decent returns if held for five years, often with tax
advantages.
Gilts. Bonds issued by the UK government, which offer a fixed income and a
fixed repayment value on a fixed date.
Index-linked gilts. Repayment value and income grow in line with inflation.
Very tax-efficient, because most of the return comes in the form of capital
gain.
Guaranteed income bonds. These pay a fixed income (after basic rate tax is
deducted) and return your capital after a set period of years.
Zero dividend preference shares. Issued by investment trusts, these pay no
income but will be repaid at considerably more than their face value.
Profits are subject to capital gains (not income) tax, which few people pay.
With-profits policies. These are issued by insurance companies and should
normally only be considered if you can wait at least 10 years for your
return. They give poor value if surrendered early.
Finally, on the liquidity element of the portfolio. There can be more
imaginative choices than just the building society. Money market funds offer
competitive rates, and two (Fidelity and M &amp; G) give chequebooks to those
with over Pounds 5,000. A Tessa gives tax-free interest if held for five
years; all that happens if you withdraw money early is that you pay the tax
you would have paid in the first place.
It makes sense to get financial advice, although make sure that you know on
what terms you are paying for it. Most FT readers should consider paying a
fee, so that the adviser is paid by you, rather than by the product
provider. But whether fees or commissions, go to an independent adviser in
preference to a tied agent who just works for one company.
</TEXT>
