<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (11): Recovery is delayed by a sick
economy - Japan's Stock Market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TOKYO stock market has suffered a heavy fall since reaching its peak
just before the close of 1989. Since then, it has dropped by about 57 per
cent, compared with a rise of about 12 per cent for the UK stock market and
an 18 per cent rise in US equities.
Since the start of 1990, the Nikkei average has underperformed the Dow Jones
and the FT-SE 100 by more than 60 per cent. But despite this
underperformance, analysts and fund managers do not believe that Tokyo's
long-awaited recovery has begun.
Poor earnings growth, a slowing economy, falling property prices and an
increase in bad loans outweigh the potential benefits of a further cut in
interest rates this year and last year's official measures to support the
stock market.
The state of the Japanese economy is the main reason for investors to be
cautious. In mid-January, Mr Noboru Hatakeyama, vice-minister at the
ministry of international trade and industry and one of the country's top
economic policymakers, warned that the economy would only begin to recover
in the autumn at the earliest.
Mr Rod Birkett, fund manager of Flemings Japanese Investment Trust, believes
that the Japanese economy may not show signs of a sustained recovery until
possibly 1994. Furthermore, the stock market will have difficulty in
pre-empting a recovery in the economy, because of the loss of confidence
among investors.
However, he believes that 1993 might still provide a good opportunity to buy
Japanese equities, especially for investors prepared to take a longer-term
view of the market. He would hope to be fully invested later on this year -
the cash position of his Pounds 180m trust is just under 5 per cent at
present.
Mr Robert Hook, a senior fund manager of Japanese equities at Prolific Asset
Management, is wary of the market at present, because it is being
artificially supported by public money, as a result of the government's
package to help the stock market. He also finds it difficult to find value
in a market which he believes does not yet reflect the fundamentals of the
economy.
The views of fund managers are broadly in line with the forecasts of
brokers. SG Warburg, in its 1993 outlook, says that the potential rewards in
overweighting the Japanese market at current levels seem rather meagre,
while the risks remain high. Furthermore the stock market's valuations (for
example, it is trading on a prospective price/earnings ratio of more than
50, compared with around 16 for the US, about 13 for the UK and just under 9
for Hong Kong) do not appear inviting to the broker, unless there is a more
rapid pick-up in profits than it thinks likely.
Warburg agrees that the declared buying interest of public funds is playing
a blocking role, but this cannot provide a new impetus for equities on its
own. Therefore the broker forecasts a decline in the market indices of 20-25
per cent over the first four to six months of 1993, and looks for the market
to bottom in the second quarter.
James Capel is more positive about Japan than other brokers. In its 1993
outlook, it believes that, after a dismal 1992, the market may already have
seen the bottom. The broker expects further gains in 1993, with a target of
about 20,000 on the Nikkei for the year-end, and about 1,540 on the Topix
index. The indices currently stand at 16,500 and 1,270 respectively.
Capel agrees that the market's supply-and-demand problems are not yet behind
it, and expects continued selling by tokkin, or specified money trusts, this
year, although not as heavy as in the first quarter of 1992.
Nevertheless, Capel believes the gradual recovery of the Japanese economy,
combined with a more tangible improvement in the US, will make 1993 a good
year for the electrical sector. Warburg also sees some pockets of optimism
in the Tokyo market. For example, it believes that the ratings of
non-financial shares, such as capital goods producers and consumer product
manufacturers, are not too demanding.
Prolific's Mr Hook believes the restructuring of the Japanese economy, as
manufacturing companies turn away from a policy of making wafer-thin profit
margins on high-volume sales towards one of greater profitability and
competitiveness, will provide a longer-term investment theme for investors.
Fleming's Mr Birkett says an improvement in Japanese companies' return on
equity over the 1990s will feed through into better profits, which will in
turn reduce the p/e ratios of individual stocks. At the beginning of this
year, return on equity in Japan was a low 4.5 per cent, compared with 15 per
cent in the US.
</TEXT>
