<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (10): Losses spur the pace of
innovation - Insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL, ECONOMIC and technological pressures are transforming the UK's
insurance industry and leading to significant changes in the price, range
and quality of home, motor and other consumer products and the way in which
they are bought.
Since the mid-1980s, the industry has been subject to an onslaught of
competitive pressures.
The final abandonment of the insurance companies' cartel in 1985 - the
so-called tariff system - ushered in a period of intense competition among
large composite insurance groups - Royal Insurance, Sun Alliance, Guardian
Royal Exchange, Commercial Union, General Accident, Eagle Star and Norwich
Union.
UK companies were particularly anxious to retain and increase market share
as a result of the opening of the European insurance market and the entry
into the UK of giant European companies such as Allianz and L'Union des
Assurances de Paris.
The resulting price competition drove premium rates downwards, especially in
higher margin commercial insurance (the policies bought by businesses rather
than individuals), leaving the industry ill-prepared for a surge of claims
from storms and subsidence in 1990 and 1991.
The recession led to an increase in claims for theft and arson. Worse still,
the collapse of the property market and the downward spiral in house prices
led to wholly unexpected claims on mortgage indemnity policies - a class of
insurance policy sold to banks and building societies to protect mortgage
loans, traditionally regarded as virtually risk-free by insurers.
These factors contributed to a cyclical downturn in the industry, which left
almost every insurer nursing heavy losses in 1990 and 1991, when pre-tax
losses for the UK industry amounted to more than Pounds 2bn. For some
companies, such as Royal Insurance and Sun Alliance, these losses were the
first ever sustained.
The fall in the equity and property markets - especially during 1991,
because of the Gulf War - made matters even worse, as it reduced the size of
the insurance companies' own assets. Solvency is a concept used by
regulators and insurance brokers (who are essentially professional insurance
buyers) to measure the financial health of insurance companies. It compares
a company's capital base with its insurance liabilities (in the technical
jargon, net assets as a percentage of non-life premium income).
Because insurance companies paid for losses from their own reserves, and
because the value of their investments in shares and buildings fell, the
solvency of most insurers has fallen.
One company, Municipal Mutual Insurance, the ninth largest in the country,
has been forced to withdraw from the market. The industry as a whole is keen
to raise fresh capital by issuing more shares.
On top of these economic pressures, a wave of technological innovation has
made it easier for new companies to enter the market, and forced insurance
companies to re-examine their traditional ways of doing business. Because so
many of their day-to-day operations concern the routine processing of
information, the introduction to the market of cheaper and more powerful
computers has had a particularly important effect.
Computers have allowed insurance companies to make their 'backroom'
operations (filing, claims processing etc) more efficient. In addition, they
give underwriters access to more information more quickly about the risks
they insure and the claims that have resulted. This should allow insurers to
price risks more accurately.
The greatest amount of innovation has occurred so far in the motor insurance
market. Using advanced computer software and telephone systems, companies
such as Direct Line, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland, have
developed direct sales techniques which bypass the insurance broker, the
industry's traditional middleman. Direct Line and its imitators advertise
their products through carefully planned television and advertising
campaigns, and employ relatively low-grade clerical staff to underwrite
insurance and sell policies over the telephone.
Brokers have reacted to this threat by developing their own networks and
streamlining their links with companies to increase their efficiency. Chains
such as AA Insurance Services and Swinton offer telephone sales services,
supplementing their extensive networks of high street branches and offering
instant price quotes.
For the consumer, this combination of economic pressures and technological
innovation has produced a mixed picture. On the one hand, the cost of
insurance has increased sharply in the past two years as insurers have
sought to recover from recent heavy losses. On the other, insurers have
become much more selective in their pricing, more and more relating premium
levels to smaller and smaller classes of risk.
For example, until 1991, the price of household insurance tended to be
around Pounds 2 per Pounds 1,000 of rebuilding cost, with relatively few
variations between companies. But in the past 18 months, each of the
companies has introduced a range of rating bands, with the price of
insurance varying from Pounds 1.80 to Pounds 4 per Pounds 1,000, depending
on a property's exposure to subsidence or storm risk.
Further changes are on the cards as Direct Line and similar sales companies
enter the market. Building societies and banks sell over 50 per cent of
insurance policies in the UK, receiving in return sizeable commissions of
over 30 per cent in some cases. By reducing these costs of distribution,
both brokers and direct writers can offer cheaper products.
Increasingly, insurers are competing in terms of the service they offer as
well as price. For example, by using telephone networks and computer
systems, companies have introduced so-called 'help lines', offering
consumers assistance when a claim occurs. In addition, some companies now
offer access to legal advice as part of insurance policies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6282 Investment Advice.
    P6311 Life Insurance.
    P6331 Fire, Marine, and Casualty Insurance.
</IN>
