<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (8): Keep awake to read the small
print - Guarantees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORD 'guarantee' seems to give many investors the ability to sleep
soundly at nights. Over the past year, there have been guaranteed products
in the fields of fixed interest, property and equities.
But investors should never forget one thing; the guarantee is only as good
as the institution offering it. A prime example was Birmingham Capital
Trust, a small banking institution, which guaranteed to pay no less than 12
per cent per annum over five years on its tax-exempt special savings account
(Tessa).
At the end of 1992, however, the bank wrote to Tessa holders, telling them
that 'due to a major erosion of the capital base of the company' the account
would be shut down. Investors were recommended to switch to the Dudley
Building Society, which was then offering a much lower (and variable) return
of 8.5 per cent.
So when offered a guarantee (especially one that lasts a long time),
investors should carefully consider whether the company will be strong
enough to honour it.
A second point is to make sure what exactly is being guaranteed. The
Scottish Widows Monthly Bond, offered at the end of last year, was a case in
point. The advertisement offered up to 9.2 per cent per annum net for five
years - and said: 'We can only guarantee these rates on the first Pounds 15m
invested.'
But the 'guarantee' on this product applied only to the income, not the
capital. The advertisement did contain the standard warning: 'The value of
stock market investment may fall as well as rise, and investors may not get
back the full amount originally invested.'
In fact, the Scottish Widows product consisted of a combination of an
annuity and a personal equity plan. For investors to receive all their
capital back, the Pep would have to grow at 13 per cent per annum. That is a
steep growth target. If the Pep failed to grow at all (by no means
impossible, as many investors will have found in the past), the capital loss
would be 40 per cent.
Investors could have gleaned these facts by careful study of the product
literature, but many may not have done so. The lesson is: do not rely on the
word 'guarantee' in an advertisement. Read the small print.
Some guaranteed products are relatively straightforward:
Guaranteed income bonds (see also B for Bonds) are issued by insurance
companies, pay a fixed income over a number of years, and repay your lump
sum at the end of the period. This income is paid net of tax, and cannot be
reclaimed by basic rate taxpayers. The backing for the guarantee comes from
the Policyholders Protection Act, which will pay 90 per cent of the value of
the fund if the company goes bust.
Guaranteed growth bonds are essentially the same product, except that the
income is rolled up within the bond and paid out at the end.
Once one strays into the field of guaranteed equity products, things become
much more complicated. Most last for a five-year period, at the end of which
they will offer your money back or a return roughly equivalent to the rise
in the FT-SE 100 Index, whichever is the greater.
But the market is evolving all the time, with some products now offering an
income facility, others giving the chance to lock in gains as they occur,
and some allowing the investors to make early withdrawals.
These products may well appeal to those cautious investors plunging into the
equity markets for the first time. But they should remember two key points:
You do not get something for nothing. The funds have to pay for the
guarantee. Commonly, investors have to give up the yield on the market,
which at 4-5 per cent is a significant return to lose.
Most of these products are insurance bonds and have basic-rate tax deducted.
Higher-rate taxpayers will face an extra charge and, unless they regularly
pay capital gains tax, they should be better off with a low-charging indexed
fund.
In the case of the Business Expansion Scheme, companies have been stopped
from describing themselves as guaranteed. But in practical terms, a
guarantee is what is on offer from these schemes. These involved a BES
company buying property from an institution which agrees to buy back the
properties at a marginally higher price in five years' time. Because the
investor gets tax relief on his initial investment (turning a Pounds 10,000
investment from a top-rate payer into Pounds 6,000), returns can be very
attractive.
Much depends, of course, on the creditworthiness of the institution
concerned; if it is small and weak, it may not be able to buy back when
required. That is why the regulators attacked the word 'guarantee'. But some
schemes have third-party backing by major banks, and this 'guarantee' is
what attracts investors.
The BES is set to disappear at the end of this year, and one can expect the
market to be flooded with schemes. Financial services marketing men have as
much use for a clearance sale as any other salesman.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6282 Investment Advice.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P672  Investment Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
