<PROFILE>_AN-DBZCKAHGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (7): Be sure it's your tune the
piper plays - Fees v Commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO FINANCIAL advice comes free. One way or another, you will have to pay for
it.
This may grate, but advisers need to earn a living. The problem is how they
should do this.
There are two basic methods of remuneration: fees, where you pay the adviser
according to time and effort spent; and commissions, where the product
provider pays the adviser a proportion of the money spent on the product.
Theoretically, as far as the consumer is concerned, there is no contest. An
adviser paid by fee is your agent, with no incentive to offer any particular
product or any particular company. Thus, he or she can offer genuinely
'independent' advice.
A commission-charging adviser, on the other hand, is being paid by the
product provider, and has a natural bias to be its agent, and not yours.
Such advisers may not suggest non-commission products such as National
Savings or investment trusts to their clients.
What makes this worse is that commissions vary from product to product and
from company to company. Until 1989 they were capped by the Maximum
Commissions Agreement, but this was abolished, in a move which the industry
bitterly opposed, and commissions have risen since.
Also, when buying from direct sales forces, or from tied agents of insurance
companies, such as most building societies, the system of incentives for
sales staff can be camouflaged in the figures. You have the right to ask an
independent adviser how much commission he is receiving, but this does not,
unfortunately, apply to those who can only sell the products of one company.
In practice, however, the commission-charging system has survived intact
because many consumers will not write out a cheque to an intermediary. They
are certainly unlikely to write out cheques for amounts equivalent to the
sums the insurance companies are paying advisers in commission.
Fee-charging advisers have a market among better-off people who are used to
paying fees for lawyers and accountants, but their chances of expanding must
await a change in attitude by the British public.
How much commission do you pay on the standard investment products?
Endowment Policies: According to a survey conducted last year by Lautro, the
life assurance regulator, the average commission on a 25-year
mortgage-linked endowment with Pounds 50 monthly premiums in 1991 was Pounds
570 to a tied agent (a category which includes most building societies) and
Pounds 498 to an independent adviser. Total premiums in the first year would
be Pounds 600. Total range was, for tied agents, from Pounds 435.60 to
Pounds 641.52, and for independents from Pounds 419.76 to Pounds 578.16.
This tempts advisers both to sell an endowment, when a repayment mortgage on
its own will usually not yield any commission at all, and to recommend one
high commission company rather than another. The law does not allow an
adviser to recommend one company rather than another solely because it pays
a higher commission, but it is hard to believe that life offices would offer
more commission unless it had an effect.
Personal Pensions: Commissions again reach high levels. Lautro's survey
found that the commission on the average 25-year individual personal pension
is 62 per cent of the first year's premium. For 10-year pensions it would
take a bite of 29 per cent. Again, commissions are higher if you go to a
tied agent, such as most building society - 69 per cent of first year's
premiums were taken from 25-year pensions, and 34 per cent from 10-year
plans. Facilities for rebating commission, or reinvesting it in the
contract, tend to be more advanced than they are for endowments.
Single-premium Bonds: The Lautro survey revealed that, out of Pounds 1,000,
Pounds 52 would probably go to an appointed agent and Pounds 52 to an
independent adviser.
Unit Trusts: Three percentage points of the front-end charge are meant as
commission for the adviser. Lautro found that the average commission out of
an investment of Pounds 1000 was Pounds 32 for tied agents and Pounds 31 for
independents. The same norm applies to unit trust Peps. This is a steady
industry standard, although Lazards and Murray Johnstone have cut their
front-end charge by removing the commissions. Note the hefty incentive this
provides to offer single premium bonds, life assurance element and all,
rather than unit trusts, and endowments, rather than Peps, for mortgage
repayment.
Investment Trusts: Normally you would only pay a brokers fee for making the
transaction. However, several investment trust managers have taken to
offering 3 per cent commission to independent advisers. This has helped them
in the race against unit trusts in recent years.
Gilts: You can buy them through the National Savings Stock Register at the
post office, and no commission as such is payable. The administration charge
is Pounds 1 for the first Pounds 250 you buy, and 50p for each subsequent
Pounds 125 on top of this.
National Savings: No commission is payable. You can buy them from a post
office, for no charge.
Tessas: No commission is payable - they are normally bought direct from a
building society, whose expenses have been taken into account in the rate of
interest on offer.
Arm yourself with this information when going to an adviser. But there are
also can be dangers in the 'fee-charging' system. If someone charges you a
fee, make sure you know the exact basis on which fees will be charged in
advance. If they advise you to buy a commission-charging product, make sure
that commission is accounted for  - there is certainly no merit in paying
both fees and commission.
Also, commission is only one of the factors behind your choice of
investment. It may be worth paying high commissions for performance, but you
should have strong evidence of good performance before paying over-the-odds;
other things being equal, low charges should boost the performance of your
investment in the long run.
</TEXT>
<XX>
