<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (6): Inheritance tax may be
avoidable - Estate Planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE LAW allows people to leave a considerable estate
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Pounds 150,000 - before any tax at all is payable, and many might feel this
is sufficiently generous. The best measures to mitigate the inheritance tax
burden for your heirs tend to involve placing a lot of trust in them, which
some parents might not be prepared to do.
Two or three years ago there was a spate of IHT 'plans', as the tax seemed
likely to catch more people. Now, as house prices - the main constituent of
most estates - fall while the threshold for paying the tax increases, many
are slipping back out of the IHT net. The longer lives secured by modern
medicine are also taking their toll on the value of estates left at death,
particularly when a few years are spent in expensive residential care. There
may be more point in ensuring that you have enough money to pay for this
care during your lifetime, than in limiting the IHT payable on whatever
estate is left.
However, those who want to take action against IHT can take heart from the
fact that it is a very easy tax to avoid.
The basic allowances are as follows:
You can leave as much as you like to your spouse - all bequests to a
marriage partner are outside the IHT net, and all other allowances are in
addition to this.
The threshold before IHT is payable on an estate is Pounds 150,000. No tax
will be payable if Pounds 150,000 is left to an heir and the rest of the
estate is left to a spouse.
Over and above these, 'potentially exempt transfers' can be made. These are
gifts made to heirs (or anyone else) during the donor's lifetime. If the
donor survives for seven years, no IHT will be payable on these. If death
intervenes within seven years, then there could be an IHT liability - this
tapers off, depending on how long the donor survives.
On top of these provisions, there are annual exemptions:
A gift of up to Pounds 3,000 can be given each year to an individual,
completely free of IHT liability. This can only be carried forward by one
tax year, so those who have not made such a gift for IHT purposes before can
give a maximum of Pounds 6,000 in the first tax year.
A limitless number of 'small gifts' of up to Pounds 250 per tax year can
also be given away. If you had 20 people to whom you wanted to make gifts,
you could therefore give Pounds 5,000 completely free of IHT.
Once all these exemptions have been accounted for, heirs will have to pay 40
per cent of any excess in tax. From an estate of Pounds 1m where no action
had been taken, therefore, Pounds 340,000 would be payable in tax (40 per
cent of Pounds 850,000).
If you do not want your heirs to be burdened with this there are two broad
ways to proceed - either by using life assurance policies, or through
trusts.
The route of least resistance is to insure your life for the amount of IHT
which you expect your heirs to have to pay. If you take out a whole-of-life
policy, written in trust, your heirs are at least guaranteed not to have to
be out of pocket. However, life insurance for the elderly is not cheap, so
this could make quite a dent in the value of the estate.
A variation on this is to give your money away as a potentially exempt
transfer, and then take out a seven-year term insurance policy. If you die
within the seven-year time limit, therefore, your heirs' tax liability will
be covered. However, the life insurers will pay nothing if you survive more
than seven years.
Still another possibility is to buy a whole-of-life policy, along with an
annuity. All money paid into an annuity is automatically outside your
estate, as it officially belongs to the life company, and the annuity income
payments can then be used to pay the premiums for the whole-of-life policy.
Taking this route could, however, be over-generous to a salesman paid by
commission only.
A more complicated route to estate-planning, which involves paying less in
life insurance commission, involves setting up a trust. Inheritance
tax-planning trusts are typically 'gift and loan', where some money is given
to the trust but a larger proportion is only loaned. Profits made by the
trust on the money loaned to it should be immune from IHT, although the
precise limits are controversial.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
