<PROFILE>_AN-DBZCKAHEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (5): If you Pep them, watch the
charges - Dividends
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY PEOPLE make the mistake of thinking that owning shares is all about
capital gains. In fact, dividends are vitally important.
Broadly speaking, share prices do no more than keep up with inflation over
the long term. In real (after inflation) terms, BZW figures show that share
prices were no higher at the end of 1992 than they were at the end of 1968.
The real return to investors thus comes in the form of dividend income.
BZW's calculations show that the real return to investors from shares since
1919 has been a gross 7.3 per cent per annum. If you assume that dividends
will grow in line (over the long term) with GDP, then a rough and ready
calculation is to say this real return from equities consists of the average
dividend yield of 5 per cent, plus dividend growth of 2 per cent.
The compounding effect of such growth rates can be remarkable. The BZW
figures show that someone with a gross dividend income of Pounds 1,000 in
1978 would have seen it grow to Pounds 4,687 by 1992.
But the 1980s were a remarkable period. The UK was emerging from a decade
when corporate profits were depressed, dividend growth was restricted and
inflation was high. Dividends actually fell by 25 per cent in real terms
between 1970 and 1978.
So the 1980s may have represented a 'catch-up' period. As so often happens,
the 1990s has seen yet another change in mood. According to BZW, dividends
actually fell in nominal terms in 1992 - for the first time since 1973.
The long economic boom of the 1980s made companies confident about their
ability to pay out dividends. The 'cover' ratio - the extent to which
current profits are sufficient to pay dividends - has dropped below 2, well
below the historical average. Many were caught out by the depth of the
current recession and have been forced to cut dividends, or not pay them at
all; a move which normally causes unpopularity among investors.
This suggests that any recovery in profits in the 1990s will be used to
rebuild dividend cover rather than to increase payouts substantially.
Nevertheless, now that UK interest rates have fallen to such low levels,
investors are starting to see dividend yields as a source of immediate
income.
At the start of February, the dividend yield on the FT-A All-Share Index was
4.3 per cent, compared with base rates of 6 per cent.
If held within a personal equity plan, dividends are tax-free. So the net
income return from a Pep for a top-rate taxpayer could easily beat the
return from a building society account as well. Add in the possibility of
capital growth as well and it is easy to see why Peps could prove popular.
Much depends on the Pep charges, however. If the annual charge is 1 per cent
plus VAT (1.175 per cent), then a Pep will have to yield 4.7 per cent for
the tax savings of a basic-rate payer to outweigh the charge. For a top-rate
taxpayer, the break-even yield is around 2.94 per cent.
The market is becoming ever more competitive, however, and managers are
showing willingness to be flexible in their charging structures. By creating
hybrid products, with part of the portfolio invested in bonds and the bulk
in equities, managers can offer Peps with attractive yields and reasonable
levels of security.
Cazenove launched a Pep in early February, for example, which invested in
utility stocks (such as water and electricity) and in bonds. With a yield of
7 per cent (after allowing for the annual management charge of 0.5 per
cent), the initial charge of 0.2 per cent plus Pounds 35 makes little dent
on the tax attractions to those who can invest the full Pounds 6,000 Pep
allowance.
But investors need to be cautious of too high a dividend yield. This
normally signals a high risk investment, and what investors gain in income,
they can lose in capital. Furthermore, the fact that an individual share is
on an above-average yield often signals that the market expects the dividend
not to grow, or to be cut, in the near future.
Sometimes capital loss can be built into the structure of the investment, as
with some of the income shares of split-capital trusts. In some cases, these
income shares will have no value at all when the trust is wound up; and so
the shares closely resemble an annuity. In other cases, the repayment value
of the income shares is dependent on the trust receiving high investment
returns, making the shares highly speculative.
So when choosing a Pep to take advantage of dividend returns, investors
should look very carefully at both charges and the nature of the underlying
investments. The good news is that there are attractive packages around, and
that history has shown that dividends are a reliable source of income
growth.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P672  Investment Offices.
    P6282 Investment Advice.
</IN>
