<PROFILE>_AN-DBZCKAHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (3): A good bet if inflation remains
low - Bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BONDS ARE suddenly attracting the attention of British investors. The reason
is simple: bond returns are now higher than those available on cash in
building societies. In the jargon of finance, this is called a positive
yield curve.
A bond is just a tradable IOU with the issuer agreeing to pay interest and
to repay the capital on maturity. In Europe and in the US, it is very common
for private investors to own them.
But in Britain, high inflation has in the past destroyed the value of bond
holdings. Investors are hoping that the current conditions of low inflation
and high real (after inflation) yields will make bond buying more profitable
this time.
The key thing to understand about bonds is the yield. The running yield is
the relationship between the interest rate and the market price, calculated
by dividing the former by the latter. A bond which has an interest rate of
10 per cent and a price of 80 has a running yield of 12.5 per cent. If the
price rises to 125, then the running yield falls to 8 per cent. So as prices
rise, yields fall and vice versa.
What complicates the calculations is that bonds will eventually be repaid at
face value (normally expressed at 100). So someone who buys a bond at 80 can
look forward to a capital gain of 20 if he holds the bonds till maturity.
The combination of capital gain or loss to maturity plus interest is called
the gross yield to redemption. The redemption yields for government bonds
(gilts) are shown every day in the FT.
Bonds priced above face value have higher running yields than redemption
yields; those priced below face value have higher redemption yields than
running yields. As an example: on January 22, the Treasury 2000 issue, with
an interest rate of 13 per cent, was priced at 126 1/2 . At that price, the
running yield was 10.28 per cent and the redemption yield was 8.18 per cent.
When investors buy bonds, they have a measure of certainty. They know the
income they will receive each year, and the yield to redemption. But what
they do not know is how the price will move between purchase and maturity.
Nor do they know what inflation will do to the value of their capital while
they hold the bond.
The bond market is not a homogeneous mass, but divides into a number of
categories:
Conventional gilts. These bonds, issued by the UK government, have a fixed
return and, short of revolution, the investor is absolutely certain of
repayment. All capital gains are tax-free but income is taxable. The
cheapest way of buying gilts is via the Post Office, through not all issues
are available and you may not get the best price; you need to use a
stockbroker if you want to buy more than Pounds 10,000.
Index-linked gilts. Also issued by the government, but their repayment value
and interest payments rise in line with inflation. As a consequence, much of
the return comes in the form of (tax-free) capital gain.
UK Corporate bonds. Comparatively rare. They will offer a higher yield than
gilts, because they carry a higher risk; there is a chance, if the company
gets into trouble, that the bonds will not be repaid in full, or at all.
Overseas government bonds. The credit risk varies widely, depending on the
country. But as well as price fluctuations due to interest-rate changes, the
investor also faces an exchange-rate risk; if the foreign currency
depreciates against the pound, the value of the bond will fall in sterling
terms. Broadly speaking, if another government's bonds are yielding more
than gilts, that is because the credit risk is significantly higher, or the
foreign exchange markets expect the country's currency to decline. Costs of
dealing in such bonds can be high, so they are best bought via a fund.
Overseas corporate bonds. Have all the characteristics of overseas
government bonds, with extra credit risk thrown in.
Guaranteed income bonds. Not tradable like the bonds in all the above
categories, but they do offer a fixed return over a fixed period. They are
issued by insurance companies and interest is paid net of tax (and cannot be
reclaimed); security is provided by the Policyholders' Protection Act, which
guarantees 90 per cent of the investment, should the insurance company get
into difficulty.
Permanent insurance-bearing shares. Not strictly speaking, bonds at all, but
have some of the same characteristics; that is, they pay a fixed rate of
interest and are tradeable. They are issued by building societies. Two very
important points, however: they will never be repaid, and so have no
redemption value; and if the building society goes bust, they come a long
way down in the list of creditors to be repaid. As usual, therefore, the
higher returns they offer do involve higher risk.
Bond funds.
For those who do not want the headache of buying bonds directly, bond funds
offer an alternative. Most are unit trusts, and by investing in a portfolio
of bonds, aim to provide the investor with income and/or capital growth.
Investors need to be aware that the higher the yield on offer, the greater
the risk of capital loss.
One disadvantage of a gilt fund is that profits are subject to capital gains
tax - not the case if the investor had bought government securities
directly. But a further point is that the investor must pay management fees.
These have fallen over the past year or so, with some managers making no
initial charge, but others still charge 5 per cent. Annual charges tend to
be around 1 per cent.
The task for the investor is to decide whether the manager's expertise more
than makes up for the fees. The top performing domestic bond funds over the
five years to January 1 were: Abbey Capital Reserve, Whittingdale Short
Dated Gilt and Kleinwort Benson Gilt Yield; the average return for the
sector over the five year period was 38.3 per cent (offer-to-bid with net
income reinvested).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6282 Investment Advice.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-6897</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DBZCKAHBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930226
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / A-Z of Personal Finance (2): Tough times increase the
charges risk - Accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS HAVE had a tough year, during which they have been lambasted over high
charges and poor service. The introduction of charges by Robert Fleming/Save
&amp; Prosper on its current account for those in credit is seen as the
beginning of the end of free banking.
One of the measures taken by banks and building societies to weather the
recession has been a widening of their margins. This has affected borrowers
more than savers (see L for loans).
The main effect of the recession on savers has been a greater need to be
vigilant about their accounts so that they do not find themselves paying
unnecessary charges.
Competitiveness in the banking sector has increased the number of services,
such as telephone and postal banking as well as the range of different
accounts, for example, high interest cheque accounts. Customers can enjoy a
greater choice but they must also do more work to select the right kind of
bank and type of account for their needs.
To do this, anyone with a bank account should put himself into one of two
categories: the customer who does not expect to need an overdraft and the
one who foresees going into the red intermittently.
If you are in credit.
Interest-bearing current accounts. The level of overdraft rates is not a
concern. Instead, you can choose between the interest-bearing current
accounts of banks and building societies. These should provide features such
as a Pounds 100 cheque guarantee/debit card, credit cards and good service.
Almost all banks and building societies give tiered rates of interest, but
some give significantly better returns on higher deposits.
The difference can be startling. For example, earlier this month net
percentage rates on current accounts with Pounds 10,000 were Abbey National
Current (0.38); Bank of Scotland BankSave Plus (2.48); Britannia React 365
(3.19); Co-op Pathfinder (4.38); First Direct (1.13); Lloyds Gold (2.25);
Midland Meridian (2.40); Woolwich Current (2.93); Robert Fleming/Save &amp;
Prosper (3.38).
It is important to check the terms and conditions of the accounts. For
example, the Co-op Pathfinder account offers standing orders and direct
debit, but has no chequebook facility. There are monthly charges on the
Lloyds Gold and Midland Meridian accounts, if the balance falls below Pounds
1,000.
First Direct and Robert Fleming/Save &amp; Prosper do not have branches but are
telephone banking operations.
High-interest cheque accounts. These aim to pay higher rates of interest on
large deposits than interest-bearing current accounts, but they usually
require a large minimum balance.
There may also be a minimum withdrawal size and many, such as Caledonian
Bank's Hica, do not offer a cheque guarantee card or direct debit. Instead,
Caledonian's Hica pays a flat rate of interest which is unusual, because
most Hicas pay lower rates on smaller deposits.
These accounts are designed to complement rather than replace current
accounts, but some customers may find it more convenient to operate a
current account alongside a savings account (see V for Variable rate
investments).
Other types of account include those provided by Midland's Orchard and Royal
Bank of Scotland's Balanced Banking, which allow customers an automatic
transfer of funds between a choice of accounts.
If you are overdrawn. If you are likely to be overdrawn either consistently
or at periodic intervals, charges are the most important consideration.
Banks and building societies have been ruthless about widening their margins
and, in their attempt to retain savers in the face of lower base rates, they
are happier to pass the cost on to borrowers.
Accounts which pay high rates of interest to those in credit are the ones
most likely to have draconian charges for those who go into the red.
Overdraft charges are in two parts. The first is the annual rate of
interest, which will be substantially higher on an unauthorised overdraft
than on one which has been arranged. For example, National Westminster's
authorised overdraft rate on its current account is 19.2 per cent per annum
and 32.9 per cent for an unauthorised overdraft. The Co-op is unusual in
making no difference in rates between an authorised and unauthorised
overdraft.
However, customers will be less aware of the second set of charges. These
may be additional fees for exceeding an arranged overdraft, as well as
charges for sending out a warning letter or bouncing a cheque. Transaction
charges may also be made.
Some banks, such as Lloyds and Royal Bank of Scotland, allow the customer to
be overdrawn by Pounds 100 before imposing overdraft fees.
In its last survey of current accounts, Which?, the Consumer Association's
monthly, found that the banks which came out best in terms of overall
satisfaction to the customer were Abbey National, Co-op, First Direct, Royal
Bank of Scotland and Yorkshire Bank. Those that were above average were Bank
of Scotland, Girobank, Halifax and Nationwide. The ones voted worst were
Lloyds, Midland and NatWest.
Moneyfacts (0692 500765) and Blay's Moneymaster (0753 880482) are monthly
publications which include details of bank and building society interest
rates on accounts, credit cards, Tessas and mortgages.
</TEXT>
