<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: International Wheat Council
says ex-Soviet republics seeking to expand use of barter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Russia and other former Soviet republics in difficulty with grain payments
are seeking to expand the use of barter, according to the International
Wheat Council, writes David Blackwell. Sales have already been fixed under
the US Export Enhancement Program (EEP) - mostly in exchange for cotton from
Uzbekistan.
Australia, Canada, Finland and Turkey are thought to have held talks on
barter deals, the IWC says in its latest grain market report. The
Australians are believed to have been offered 40,000 tonnes of aluminium in
exchange for wheat.
However, with the exception of the US, the parties concerned 'are reluctant
to reveal details of any possible arrangements' as they involve price
exposure on both sides of a transaction. Traders need to cover themselves
for commodities that they are unfamiliar with.
The fact that most commodities are in plentiful supply on the international
market at relatively low prices further complicates any attempts to expand
barter trade, the IWC suggests.
</TEXT>
