<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / UK Company News: TransAtlantic slips to Pounds 60.7m -
Contribution from Sun Life nearly doubled to Pounds 36.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANSATLANTIC Holdings, the property and life assurance group which obtained
a London stock market listing last year, yesterday announced a marginal fall
in pre-tax profits from Pounds 61.2m to Pounds 60.7m for the year to
December 31.
Earnings per share fell to 9.93p compared with 14.52p in 1991, reflecting
increases in the amount of unrelieved advance corporation tax and reduced
interest capitalisation.
A recommended final dividend of 6p raises the total for the year to 12p,
against 11.45p in 1991.
TransAtlantic is owned jointly by Liberty Life, the South African life
assurance company, and Union des Assurances de Paris, France's largest
insurer. It owns 50 per cent of Sun Life Holdings, the UK life insurer, and
Capital &amp; Counties, the property company.
Mr Donald Gordon, chairman, said he was 'especially encouraged by the
performance of Capital &amp; Counties' regional shopping centre property
portfolio, which has demonstrated strong signs of buoyancy both in turnover
and an improved market share of retail trade'.
Income from property investment amounted to Pounds 67.9m (Pounds 60m), while
proceeds from property trading were Pounds 3.5m (Pounds 2.2m).
Administrative expenses fell to Pounds 11.7m (Pounds 12.6m). Income from Sun
Life nearly doubled to Pounds 36.7m (Pounds 18.7m).
Interest payable amounted to Pounds 35.7m, against Pounds 7.4m in 1991,
reflecting a significant reduction in interest capitalised on property
development projects from Pounds 32.4m to Pounds 11.6m, principally because
interest capitalisation ceased at June 30 1991 on the Thurrock Lakeside
Shopping Centre development.
Share capital and reserves increased from Pounds 775m to Pounds 948m. The
value of investment properties rose to Pounds 1.05bn (Pounds 1.01bn), with
the advance reflecting a large rise in the valuation from Pounds 325m to
Pounds 380m of Thurrock Lakeside, which amounts to 40 per cent of
TransAtlantic's property portfolio.
Special assumptions were made about the exceptional turnover rent potential
of the Thurrock development. Pounds 25.9m of the increase was due to
exchange rate fluctuations.
Separately, Sun Life yesterday reported a 12 per cent increase in pre-tax
profits to Pounds 46.7m (Pounds 41.7m), although new premium income fell
marginally to Pounds 1.49bn compared with Pounds 1.5bn in 1991. New single
premiums amounted to Pounds 1.4bn (Pounds 1.41bn), with regular premiums
falling by 3 per cent to Pounds 85.6m.
</TEXT>
