<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / UK Company News: Woolwich Building Socy turns in rise to
Pounds 149m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOOLWICH Building Society, the fourth largest with assets of Pounds 23.3bn,
yesterday disclosed a 9.5 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds 149.3m,
compared with Pounds 136.4m, despite doubling its provisions for possible
bad debts in the depressed housing market.
Woolwich made new provisions of Pounds 144.7m (Pounds 72.4m), raising its
total provisions to Pounds 207m. About 40 per cent of the rise in provisions
was estimated to relate to the Town &amp; Country Building Society, with which
it merged last May.
The society achieved a fall in its cost to income ratio to 50.7 per cent
(59.9 per cent). Mr John Wriglesworth, analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said
he believed this was the biggest single year fall achieved by a large
building society.
Mr Donald Kirkham, chief executive, said about 9 per cent of the society's
541,000 borrowers were in arrears. The number of properties taken into
possession fell to 3,364 (3,788). Town &amp; Country added 400 repossessions to
its stock.
The society declared an exceptional loss of Pounds 17.9m from restructuring
costs, and a Pounds 6.5m exceptional profit from tax reclaimed from the
Inland Revenue after litigation.
The aggregate net losses of the society's subsidiaries were reduced to
Pounds 24m (Pounds 30m). It managed to halve the trading loss in its estate
agency subsidiary to Pounds 11m after closing 55 branches during the year
and making 200 staff redundant.
</TEXT>
