<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Hollick splits with view of MGN board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD HOLLICK, the Labour peer, seemed isolated last night as a director of
Mirror Group Newspapers as all the other directors reaffirmed support for
the business policies of the group.
After a meeting called to remove uncertainty about the political stance of
the group, its future business direction, and the leadership of Mr David
Montgomery, the chief executive, Lord Hollick said that he could not fully
support the views of his fellow directors.
Lord Hollick, chief executive of MAI, the television, advertising and
financial services group, is a non-executive director of the popular
newspaper group.
The board yesterday confirmed its confidence in the MGN management and
authorised Mr Montgomery and his colleagues to continue the agreed strategy.
Yesterday's board meeting was also told that Mr John Talbot, the
administrator who holds 54.8 per cent of the shares in the group, has
expressed his confidence in the management and is pleased with the progress
made so far.
The latest row at the Daily Mirror blew up last week when Mr Montgomery, a
former editor of the newspaper Today, brought in Mr David Seymour as group
political editor.
That was seen as an effective demotion of Mr Alastair Campbell, the Daily
Mirror's political editor, who was close to both Mr Neil Kinnock, the former
Labour leader and to Lord Hollick. Mr Campbell resigned.
Ironically, he was yesterday appointed assistant editor of Today by Mr
Richard Stott, the newly appointed Today editor who was himself fired as
editor of the Daily Mirror by Mr Montgomery.
The MGN board emphasised that there never would be any question of the group
changing its left-of-centre political stance.
Sir Robert Clark, MGN chairman, said: 'I am glad that all the other 10
directors, as well as our controlling shareholder, have today reinforced
their support for the management and for the policies we have been pursuing.
Untrue speculation can now be laid to rest.'
Lord Hollick said: 'I have raised a number of concerns. The chairman has
informed me that the board will be looking into these matters and hopefully
steps can be taken to enable me to give my full support.'
