<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Broadcasters seem incapable of adopting a sane policy on repeats. Either
they fail to provide second screenings for programmes that clearly deserve
them, or they run so many together that viewers protest. Tonight BBC2 packs
its schedule with repeats of The Man From UNCLE, Doctor Who, Red Dwarf V,
and Heimat. True, Red Dwarf (9.00), which parodies all those space sagas
from 2001 to Aliens, is one of the best of the current comedy series, and
Heimat, (11.20) the long story of a small country town in Germany on either
side of the Second World War, is one of the most impressive drama serials
ever made. Yet it still seems barmy to show quite so many repeats on the
same evening. Two slabs of Marks and Spencer drama clash: The Good Guys runs
for an hour on ITV starting at 9.00, and Love Hurts runs for an hour on BBC1
starting at 9.30. The Good Guys with chance acquaintances Nigel Havers and
Keith Barron playing knights errant, is one of those ideas that look better
on paper than on screen. Love Hurts with ill-assorted lovers Adam Faith and
Zoe Wanamaker, wealthy plumber and trendy charity worker respectively, is
usually better.
</TEXT>
