<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Watchdog begins Granada inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Independent Television Commission will today start investigating claims
by Mrs Ann Clwyd, the shadow heritage secretary, that Granada Television is
in breach of its licence.
Sir George Russell, commission chairman, yesterday received a letter from
Mrs Clwyd asking him to consider revoking Granada's licence and accusing the
commission of being in default of its statutory duties for not taking action
sooner.
A copy of the dossier which talks of 'boardroom savagery' and a television
company 'having its heart ripped out' has also been sent to Mr Peter Brooke,
heritage secretary.
Mrs Clwyd's paper lists the number of Granada Television directors who have
left or been fired since the company bid for its new licence. Only two are
left out of 13.
A further 25 senior people 'have disappeared', the study claims, saying they
include the head of documentaries and arts, the chief engineer and head of
sound. A total of 370 staff have lost their jobs or face redundancy at
Granada.
Granada boasted in its application about its research in broadcast
engineering. But Mrs Clwyd claimed the people responsible have gone.
The commission is likely to be more interested to see whether Granada is
fulfilling the terms of its licence than carrying out the promises in its
application. In particular the commission will want to ensure that Granada
is providing a good quality service of regional broadcasting.
</TEXT>
