<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Straw demands review of grants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INDEPENDENT review of the local government grant system was urged
yesterday by Mr Jack Straw, the shadow minister for local government.
He condemned the present method of distributing council grants as 'bent and
flawed'.
The government has already conceded that standard spending assessments, its
estimates of what councils need to spend, should be thoroughly reviewed and
the process has started.
Ministers admit privately that as the system of limiting local spending
becomes increasingly dependent on SSAs, the present system might not be
'robust' enough to be a fair basis.
Next month officials of the Department of the Environment will start talking
to local authority associations about the review. The exercise will be
completed by the autumn in order to take effect in the spring next year.
But Mr Straw argued that there should be a wide review of SSAs, which should
be independent of ministers and carried out by a team chosen after
consultation with local authority associations and the Audit Commission, the
council spending watchdog.
The average council tax bill in England will be Pounds 447 per household,
according to a survey for Public Finance and Accountancy magazine and
Channel Four News based on council tax figures recommended or approved by
313 of 529 councils.
Labour-led Harlow District Council in Essex voted last night to shed 176
jobs from its total of 1,400 and to reduce its budget from Pounds 24m in
1992-93 to Pounds 18.2m in 1993-94.
</TEXT>
