<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Move on service charges rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday rejected recommendations that would have prevented
restaurants adding additional service and cover charges to bills.
A committee set up by the government to monitor the pricing provisions of
the Consumer Protection Act recommended last year that compulsory cover and
service charges should be incorporated into the prices of individual items
on the menu. This would give customers a clear idea of what the final bill
would be.
Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister, said yesterday that further
regulation was not the best way forward. She said she would prefer to rely
on a voluntary approach and customers' common sense.
She added: 'I know that payment for service charges can sometimes cause
difficulties and confusion but I am not convinced that further legislation
is the answer. We are looking to reduce rather than increase regulation. I
would prefer to rely on the responsibility and good sense of those in the
industry.'
</TEXT>
