FT  26 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Straw urges grants review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN independent review of the local government grant system was urged
yesterday by Mr Jack Straw, the shadow environment secretary, as he
condemned the present method of distributing council grants as 'bent and
flawed'.
The government has already conceded that standard spending assessments, the
government estimates of what councils need to spend, need to be thoroughly
reviewed, and the process has already started. Ministers admit privately
that as the system of limiting local spending becomes increasingly dependent
on SSAs, the present system might not be 'robust' enough to be a fair basis.
Next month, Department of the Environment officials will begin talking to
the local authority associations about the review, and the exercise will be
completed by the autumn, in order to come into effect in the spring next
year.
But Mr Straw argued that there should be a wide review of SSAs, which should
be independent of ministers and carried out by a team chosen after
consultation with local authority associations and the Audit Commission, the
local council spending watchdog.
His comments came as the local government information unit, a research unit
supported by councils and trade unions, published a report highlighting
differences in the increases in grants among councils since the mid 1980s.
The average council tax bill in England will be Pounds 447 per household,
according to a survey for Public Finance and Accountancy magazine and
Channel Four News based on council tax figures recommended or approved by
313 of 529 local authorities.
The average bill for households in Scotland will be Pounds 407 and for Wales
Pounds 258.
The figures do not include transitional relief which will further reduce
bills in areas facing steep increases.
