<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / VAT idea bad news for bookworms: The Treasury may widen tax
to increase revenue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GLUTTONOUS bookworms who feel the cold and have young families are not
looking forward to the March 16 Budget. They could be forced into
substantial increases in spending as a result of changes in value added tax
being examined at the Treasury.
Treasury officials are ploughing through their VAT calculations with an eye
to cutting Britain's mounting government deficit. One way to do this would
be to extend VAT to items such as food, books, newspapers, heating bills and
children's clothing which are exempt from taxation.
Important opposing arguments are that to increase VAT when the economy is
fragile could damage the chances of recovery. It would also add to inflation
and hit the poor particularly hard.
About a quarter of all consumer spending goes on goods and services that are
zero-rated for VAT. A further 4 per cent is spent on items which are exempt.
According to Treasury calculations charging VAT at the full 17.5 per cent
rate on all items that are either zero-rated or exempt from the tax
altogether would raise an extra Pounds 23.9bn a year.
Nobody expects Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to announce such a sweeping
measure on Budget day. He is thought more likely to decide to raise perhaps
Pounds 3bn by widening the scope of VAT through bringing a few specific
items into the tax net at a lower rate - possibly 5 per cent.
Increased taxation would help to reduce the growing gap between government
revenues and spending. This is thought likely to reach about Pounds 50bn in
1993-94 after Pounds 35bn to Pounds 40bn in the current financial year.
One relatively uncontroversial measure on VAT would be to tax domestic
energy at the full 17.5 per cent. That would raise Pounds 2.6bn a year and
could be presented as a green-tinged measure which would help to cut
emissions of carbon dioxide and reduce global warming.
Widening the scope of VAT appeals to economists who believe a substantial
element of zero-rating for such indirect taxes - which are only seen in
western Europe in the UK and the Irish republic - distorts market forces by
making certain goods and services cheaper than others.
Raising extra money from VAT would fit in with the government's moves in the
1980s to shift the fiscal burden away from taxes on income towards those on
spending. The argument is that this encourages people to increase earnings,
leading to a more dynamic economy.
As a cash-gathering vehicle VAT was, in 1979, the poor relation of income
tax. Every Pounds 1 flowing into the Treasury's coffers from income tax was
then matched by just 32p from VAT. Last year VAT's corresponding
contribution had doubled to 65p. The total raised through VAT was Pounds
37.4bn.
According to calculations by the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an
independent research group, extending VAT at the full 17.5 per cent rate to
all zero-rated goods and services would add 3.7 percentage points to the
year-on-year rise in retail price inflation if wholesalers and retailers
passed on the full effects of the extra tax to customers.
Even a modest move to increase VAT would increase the risk that underlying
inflation, now 3.2 per cent, would breach Mr Lamont's target of 4 per cent
or less during the life of this parliament.
A further disincentive for Mr Lamont is that raising VAT would hit poor
families. According to the institute's calculations, bringing all zero-rated
goods and services into the tax net would add Pounds 6.97 a week, or about 7
per cent, to the bills of those in the bottom 10 per cent by income.
Households with average incomes would have to pay Pounds 9.01 a week more,
an extra 3.5 per cent, while families in the top 10 per cent by income would
see their weekly bills increase by Pounds 10.81, a rise of less than 2 per
cent.
Supporters of an end to zero-rating say these effects could be countered by
changes in the level of benefits.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
           POTENTIAL RECEIPTS FROM LEVYING VAT ON MORE ITEMS
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
