<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Unit trust sales increase sharply: Funds under management at
record Pounds 66.1bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE unit trust industry had its best month for more than two years in
January, with net sales of Pounds 505m pushing funds under management to a
record of Pounds 66.1bn.
The sector is benefiting from the recent highs in the UK stockmarket and
from the fall in base rates, which have persuaded savers to consider
alternatives to building societies.
The effect of the 1987 stock-market crash has now dropped out of the
five-year performance statistics which unit trusts are required to show
investors.
A change in the Personal Equity Plan rules may also be helping. Until the
last Budget, investors could put only Pounds 3,000 per year into a unit
trust Pep compared with Pounds 6,000 for a general plan.
Now the full allowance can be placed in a unit trust Pep and many investors
who previously invested in direct equity-based Peps may be switching to unit
trust plans.
Since Pep sales are normally strongest in February and March, and the most
recent base rate cut was too late to affect January's sales, the positive
trend for the industry may well continue.
The best individual sector for sales was UK smaller companies, which made
net gains of Pounds 79m as investors hoped that economic recovery would
bring the long-awaited rally in small stocks.
Gross sales of unit trusts in January were Pounds 1.114bn compared with just
Pounds 555m in their recent nadir of August last year. Repurchases from
investors were Pounds 609m, giving the net figure of Pounds 505m.
If net investment ran at this rate throughout the year, the industry would
nearly match 1987's inflow of Pounds 6.33bn. Net investment for the whole of
last year was just Pounds 646m.
Further good news for the industry was that the number of unitholder
accounts, which had been declining steadily since 1987, rose from 4.35m to
4.39m.
The number of trusts also rose to 1,474 compared with 1,137 in 1987.
The Securities and Investments Board yesterday issued a consultative paper
on unit trust regulations. It was aimed mainly at redrafting the rules on
the use of futures and options.
</TEXT>
