<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / 'Whenever equities do well, people pile in': Building
societies risk losing more ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FALL in base rates since sterling left the exchange rate mechanism has
caused turmoil in the savings industry as companies compete for British
nest-eggs.
Savers who rely on building societies for income have seen returns halve
since base rates were at their peak in 1990. That has caused many to
consider the alternatives to the traditional home of the cautious British
saver - the building society.
Although building society inflows perked up to Pounds 363m in January, the
sector had a dismal 1992, with inflows of just Pounds 295m compared with
Pounds 5.8bn in 1991.
One obvious alternative home for savings is the personal equity plan, which
pays tax-free income. These can now offer better dividend yields than the
interest payments available from building societies. Recent Pep launches
from Cazenove and Hypo Foreign &amp; Colonial, for example, offered yields of 7
per cent and 10 per cent respectively. Peps were an important contributor to
the revival of unit trust sales in January. Ms Mary Blair, product
development director of Fidelity Investments, a leading unit trust
management group, says 'we have seen a lot of activity from about October of
last year, as interest rates started to come down. Recently we have seen
enquiry levels equal to those seen in 1987 before the stockmarket crash.'
Recent highs in the stock-market may be an important factor. Mr Ian
Shepherdson, UK economist at Greenwell Montagu, said: 'There is a very close
correlation between equity market performance and unit trust figures.
Whenever the equity market does well, people pile in.'
And since February and March tend to be the key months for Pep sales (ahead
of the tax year end on April 5), inflows into unit trusts may accelerate.
Another tax-driven investment is the Business Expansion Scheme. Devised as a
means of encouraging investors to back growing businesses, the scheme has
become a means of encouraging the private rented sector - and is due to be
abolished at the end of this year.
But the financial services industry has become so ingenious at exploiting
this scheme that higher-rate taxpayers can earn profits of 20 per cent in
six months at virtually no risk.
The combination of these returns and some 'Buy Now While Stocks Last'
marketing campaigns means that many scheme offers sell out within days.
Guaranteed equity products, which offer investors the rise in the FT-SE 100
Index or their money back, have also proved popular with those investors who
are nervous about the potential losses on conventional share-based schemes.
An estimated Pounds 500m has been raised by such products.
But it is not just the financial services industry which is competing for
savers' money. The government needs to raise about Pounds 1bn a week to fund
the budget deficit, and a good portion of that may have to come from
National Savings.
Building societies complained bitterly last summer about the success which
National Savings was having in competition against them. The government
retreated in the face of criticism and National Savings cut its rates and
temporarily withdrew one of its most popular products.
But National Savings is still advertising on television and did not reduce
its rates in response to the last base rate cut. Given that long term rates
are above short term rates at present - a positive yield curve in the jargon
 -some building society investors have also been persuaded to switch their
money into gilt edged stocks, which will also help the government's funding
problem.
Building societies are trying to fight back. When base rates were cut by one
percentage point in January, most societies responded with a cut of only 0.8
of a percentage point in savings rates.
Mr Jim Murgatroyd of Halifax says that the society is deliberately trying to
keep up rates for those with large sums in 90-day notice accounts.
Experience shows that around 80 per cent of the deposits come from 20 per
cent of the savers.
But societies may be limited in the degree to which they can protect their
savers at the expense of borrowers. Societies are keen to revive the housing
market, which will boost demand for mortgages and reduce their bad-debt
problem.
Mortgage rates are two percentage points above base rates (the margin was
only 0.4 of a percentage point in 1990). With margins at that level, Mr John
Wriglesworth, analyst at UBS Phillips and Drew, says societies are likely to
face increased competition in the mortgage market from the banks and
centralised lenders in 1993.
Societies thus face a squeeze from both directions.
Perhaps societies will continue to attract funds from those who are afraid
of unemployment (or have been made redundant) and who do not want to risk
the nominal value of their capital in equity-based products.
But what comes in through that door may disappear out of another as retired
savers are lured away by the government and the rest of the savings
industry.
</TEXT>
