<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Army defends Balkans job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARMY yesterday defended compulsory redundancies served on several
officers on duty in former Yugoslavia among 628 being made redundant in its
latest round of job cuts.
General Sir David Ramsbotham, the adjutant-general who is responsible for
Army personnel, said after strong criticism of the move from opposition MPs:
'We honestly could not exclude someone simply because he happened to be
serving somewhere on the 25th of February.'
Eight officers in Bosnia and Croatia were among those told by commanding
officers yesterday that they had to leave the Army. Applications for
voluntary redundancy have been accepted from nine others. A further 80
non-commissioned soldiers in former Yugoslavia are also being made
redundant.
Personnel being made redundant while in former Yugoslavia are being offered
extended notice periods because their tours of duty there will not expire
until April or May.
Normally volunteers have until October to leave the Army. Compulsory
redundancies allow for up to 12 months.
The new batch of redundancies involves a total of 6,460, including 1,308
officers.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, challenged the government at
Commons' questions over the redundancies.
'How would you feel if you were serving in the British Army under fire in
Bosnia and were handed a P45?' she asked Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the
Commons.
Mr Newton, standing in for Mr John Major while he was in the US, said the
reduction in numbers had to be handled 'in a fair and even-handed way, and
it would be much more unfair to leave troops serving in Bosnia in a state of
continuing uncertainty.'
</TEXT>
