<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / PowerGen seeks Pounds 140m pit payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN, the electricity generator, is seeking government compensation of
more than Pounds 140m over five years in return for agreeing to requests
that it keep coal stocks at existing levels to help preserve some of the
threatened 31 pits.
Its negotiating stance suggests that the government package for saving pits
may cost considerably more than the subsidy British Coal would need to
enable it to sell some of its output at world coal prices.
The British Coal subsidy is expected to be at least Pounds 500m over five
years. Any money paid to PowerGen and National Power, the other generator
for England and Wales, for holding stocks would add to this cost. National
Power's plant capacity is 50 per cent larger than PowerGen's.
PowerGen's stance on stocks is just one of the problems the government must
overcome before finding a way out of its predicament. A leaked National
Power letter showed last week that it is threatening the generators with
legislation to force them to take more coal unless they reach a voluntary
agreement.
The Department of Trade and Industry's preferred solution depends on
persuading the generators to buy 65.5m extra tonnes over five years.
Whitehall sources say PowerGen has told the government that, without
adjustments to the market, it believes the generators can take only 43m.
National Power's estimate is 40m.
Taking more than that, the generators say, would mean significant stockpiles
and the 65.5m would be achievable only if either some of the expected growth
in gas-fired or nuclear power was curtailed.
PowerGen's claim for more than Pounds 140m for stockpiling arises because it
wants to cut its stocks from 16m tonnes to 5m tonnes in the next few years.
For the government to come anywhere near its 65.5m tonnes target, the
generators would have to keep stocks at their present level and possibly
raise them.
PowerGen argues shareholders should not have to pay for the costs of
excessive stocks and that government money is needed to compensate it for
handling the stocks and for loss of interest on money tied up in stocks.
National Power stocks amount to 18m tonnes, about three times above what it
considers to be normal commercial levels.
In both companies' cases, stocks are higher than anticipated at
privatisation three years ago because of a fall in demand caused by the
recession, stronger competition from nuclear power plants and a warm winter.
National Power and PowerGen were committed to buying coal on three-year
contracts which end next month.
</TEXT>
