<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Chairman bows to criticism: Ambulance board considered
sacking senior executive Concern over lack of accountability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JIM HARRIS, chairman of the London Ambulance Service board, announced his
resignation when yesterday's report was published.
It was also announced that Mr John Wilby, the service's former chief
executive, was about to be dismissed when he resigned in October after the
computer collapse.
Mr Chris Spry, general manager of South West Thames regional health
authority, said a number of concerns had been raised with Mr Wilby at his
annual performance review in spring last year.
These included concerns about his leadership style. He said Mr Wilby would
not have been aware that the board had decided to terminate his contract
when he resigned.
Mr Harris, announcing his resignation at a press conference in the ambulance
service headquarters, said: 'It is clear that a review of the accountability
arrangements between the regional health authority and the London Ambulance
Service is necessary. In order to allow that process to proceed without
inappropriate distraction, I have decided to step aside as chairman of the
LAS board with effect from next Monday.'
It appeared from Mr Harris's replies to questions about the non-statutory
board's management of the service that it had experienced difficulties in
questioning decisions of executive directors. 'You either have to fire the
lot or accept what they say,' he said.
Yesterday's report raises important issues of managerial and public
accountability in the service and, by implica-tion, other areas of the
reformed National Health Service.
The resignations of both the chairman and former chief executive of the
service are unlikely to end discussion about whether the introduction of a
more devolved and supposedly business-like management structure may have
contributed to the computer problems not being spotted earlier.
In 1989 the government decided, as part of the process of shifting the NHS
towards locally-based management, that regional health authorities should
stop running non-core services. This led the South West Thames region, which
had managed the London Ambulance Service, to set up an arms-length board in
1990. While the regional authority remained accountable for the service the
board became responsible for day-to-day management.
The inquiry report concludes that, although lines of accountability looked
secure on paper, the board was in practice given insufficient information to
exercise its delegated responsibilities. 'Neither was it apparent that they
actively sought such information.'
The regional authority believed it important not to interfere, having set up
the board at arms-length.
Although the board and the regional authority realised there were continuing
problems with the implementation of the computer system, says the report,
both 'consistently accepted assurances' from ambulance service executive
directors that problems were being rectified and successful implementation
would be achieved. 'At no time was a full independent review commissioned of
the true state of the project.'
Union leaders say they repeatedly tried to draw concerns to the attention of
the management and board, and are calling on the entire board to join Mr
Harris in resigning.
Mr Stuart Barber, national officer of the public service union Nupe, said:
'I was personally the author of hundreds of letters to the board.'
</TEXT>
