<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Clinton-Yeltsin summit is set for early in April
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR FOREIGN STAFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENTS Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin will hold their first summit on
April 4, at a venue yet to be decided.
The announcement was made by Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state,
and Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russian foreign minister, at a joint news conference
which followed a three-hour meeting in Geneva yesterday.
Mr Clinton had hoped the meeting, which would be his first foreign trip
since becoming president, could be held sometime next month. But Mr Kozyrev
said the agenda could be so extensive as to require considerable
preparation.
The president is giving considerable attention both to finding ways of
helping Russian reforms and to continue to engage Moscow in global problems,
including bringing peace to former Yugoslavia.
He has also sought to play down talk in Washington that Mr Yeltsin's own
position was becoming increasingly parlous. A holdover Bush appointee at the
State Department was this week removed from his post for publicly suggesting
that the Russian president might no longer be a reliable partner because of
his domestic political difficulties.
On Wednesday, Mr Clinton expressed full confidence in Mr Yeltsin. The two
men met briefly last summer in Washington when Mr Clinton was still a
presidential candidate.
Mr Christopher said in Geneva that Mr Clinton had asked him to underscore
'his strong personal support for the reform policies of the Yeltsin
administration'.
Yesterday, Mr Yeltsin suffered a fresh humiliation in his battle with the
parliament chairman, Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov. Deputies refused to even discuss
Mr Yeltsin's proposals for a constitutional truce after Mr Khasbulatov told
them they were designed to limit their powers. Parliament also put off until
next Thursday a debate on whether to call a special congress to discuss the
plans.
Mr Christopher described his meeting with Mr Kozyrev as 'very good and
businesslike'. They discussed issues likely to feature on the April summit
agenda. Apart from the Middle East, these included the conflict in
ex-Yugoslavia, arms control and proliferation, and US support for Russian
economic reforms.
Mr Kozyrev said they had discussed possible co-operation in trade and
investment, the rescheduling of Russia's foreign debt and Russian sales of
conventional weapons.
</TEXT>
