<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Bundesbank in 'solidarity pact' appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German Bundesbank yesterday called for urgent action to conclude the
drawn-out negotiations in Bonn between the government, the federal states
and the opposition on a 'solidarity pact' to revive the east German economy.
In its most outspoken intervention to date, the central bank stepped up
pressure on the politicians to bury their broad differences over the size
and shape of extra taxes needed to finance soaring spending in the east.
'It is imperative that the phase of controversial discussions does not last
much longer,' said Mr Hans Tietmeyer, vice-president of the Bundesbank.
'Business needs clarity about what the whole package of measures means, and
it needs it soon.'
His call suggests a growing concern in Frankfurt at the prospect of weeks if
not months of further negotiations, causing uncertainty in the financial and
currency markets, and reducing the room for the Bundesbank to cut further
its lead interest rates.
It came as the opposition Social Democrats in the German parliament
unanimously approved proposals, including sharp increases in taxation from
July 1, and excluding any cuts in social spending - in broad contradiction
to the government's plans.
Mr Tietmeyer said public spending cuts should be no less than those proposed
by the Finance Ministry, amounting to some DM20bn (Pounds 8.4bn) a year. He
warned that the scope for further tax increases was slim from an economic
viewpoint, and that the burden of taxes and other contributions was already
high in Germany in comparison to other countries.
'A further substantial increase (in the tax burden) could damage the
long-term competitive position of German business,' he warned.
On the positive side, he said that wage developments this year had been a
victory for good sense, referring to the 3 per cent settlement for public
sector workers.
Referring to the outlook for further cuts in interest rates, Mr Tietmeyer
said that money supply growth was showing signs of the desired slowdown.
Broad money, M3, fell by 2.3 per cent in January on a seasonally adjusted,
annualised basis. Mr Tietmeyer said that the figure had ben distorted by
special factors and over 6 months January M3 had grown by 6.5 per cent.
</TEXT>
