<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Midland calls for subsidised bank loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Brian Pearse, chief executive of Midland Bank, last night called for the
government to subsidise banks to provide loans to small businesses, and to
give tax breaks to individuals to provide new forms of equity finance.
It is the first time a bank chief executive has publicly indicated that
losses suffered by banks on small business lending may lead to them limiting
their exposure to small companies unless they receive public subsidies.
Mr Pearse admitted that banks had sometimes 'pulled the rug too soon' from
under struggling small companies. But he said tax incentives were needed
because otherwise the return on equity capital for small businesses was not
high enough.
Banks have grown increasingly worried at these losses. National Westminster
this week disclosed that nearly half of its Pounds 1.3bn provisions for
possible bad debts in UK branch banking in 1992 were on loans of less than
Pounds 50,000.
Mr Pearse, speaking at the City University Business School last night, said
the government should promote a partnership between itself, businesses and
banks rather than the three 'being caught up in a rather sterile slanging
match'.
Mr Pearse called for two government innovations to attract more debt and
equity finance to small businesses:
A 'manufacturing support scheme' which would give tax breaks to individuals
to provide equity finance to small businesses. This would overcome the
obstacle of the small size of such investments and the poor risks associated
with them.
A Pounds 70m loan support scheme that would act as a form of subsidy to
industry. The government would provide support to banks to allow them to
offer medium and long-term loans to companies at 1 per cent over base rate.
Mr Pearse said that unless the government, banks and businesses found
answers to the financial difficulties facing business, failures would remain
at unacceptable levels and viable businesses would fail to achieve their
potential.
He called for a review of the tax regime to favour business owners who
retain profits within their company. At present the tax laws encourage
business owners to take out profits and put them into pension investments.
He said legislation should give suppliers a statutory right to interest on
the late payment of debt. The government should also alter the Loan
Guarantee Scheme to raise cover provided by the guarantee from 70 per cent
to 80 per cent.
The banks, for their part, should be more willing to take equity or equity
options in businesses and should make more long-term loan finance available,
Mr Pearse said.
Businesses, meanwhile, should be more willing to set aside funds to build up
equity and make more use of long-term loans.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
