<HEADLINE>
FT  26 FEB 93 / Ambulance inquiry criticises 'climate of mistrust'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday faced political embarrassment over a report
cataloguing repeated examples of flawed management leading to the collapse
of the London Ambulance Service's computer system.
Mr Jim Harris, former marketing director of British Airways, resigned as
chairman of the LAS board when the report, the result of an official
inquiry, was published, and Labour MPs called on Mr Tom Sackville, the
junior health minister responsible for the ambulance service, to join him in
resigning.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, has given health authority
officials a month to produce arrangements for better accountability in the
service.
The report's severe criticisms of LAS management follow National Audit
Office concern over inadequate financial controls in the West Midlands and
Wessex regional health authorities. It will heighten debate over whether the
new style of National Health Service management since the 1991 reforms is
contributing to difficulties.
London's computer despatch system, designed to locate and mobilise emergency
ambulances automatically, collapsed soon after going into full-scale
operation last October. It plunged the service into chaos although the
report concludes that, on the basis of coroners' court conclusions, there is
no evidence that late arrival of ambulances caused deaths. The collapse of
the computer followed prolonged criticism of the LAS for failing to attend
emergencies within official target times.
The report attacks not only what it describes as the LAS management's
high-risk strategy for introducing the computer system, but wider managerial
issues in the service. It says efforts to revitalise the LAS between 1990-92
to meet the cultural changes of the NHS reforms 'actually worsened what was
already a climate of mistrust and obstructiveness.' Management misjudged the
industrial relations climate so that
staff were alienated by changes rather than brought on board.
It was announced yesterday that the LAS board and health authority officials
had decided to terminate the contract of Mr John Wilby, the service's former
chief executive, before the computer failure in October. But he pre-empted
this by resigning.
Mrs Bottomley said that while standards had improved since last autumn,
other ambulance services provided a better service with fewer resources.
At Westminster, she and Mr Sackville came under fierce attack from London
Labour MPs, in particular for 'sweeping aside' earlier warnings that the
service was in difficulty. They also condemned Mrs Bottomley for refusing to
concede a management board of elected councillors.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said the report was 'a damning
indictment of government complacency, inaction and irresponsibility'.
Chief bows to criticism, Page 11
</TEXT>
