<DATE>930225
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Salvation Army 'knew of loss in August'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Salvation Army learned that Dollars 8.8m of its funds had gone missing
as long ago as last August, according to employees of the charity, although
it did not issue a writ to recover them until last week.
In spite of months of investigation by the accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand and
the solicitors Slaughter and May on the charity's behalf, it has yet to
trace the whereabouts of more than Dollars 6m of the missing funds.
An investigation by the Financial Times shows that Salvation Army officers
were naive in financial matters. The charity is reviewing its procedures to
try to prevent any repetition of the alleged fraud.
In early May Dollars 10m of charity funds were deposited in an account of
ASLK-CGER Bank in Antwerp, Belgium. At the time the charity was feeling
financially stretched, according to members.
An officer in charge of fund-raising, Colonel Grenville Burn, had been
persuaded by Mr Stuart Ford and Mr Gamil Naguib, two financiers, that the
charity could make a substantial profit by investing the Dollars 10m in
standby letters of credit. Other officers of the charity also approved the
proposed investment. Col Burn has since been suspended from his duties.
Approval for the opening of the Antwerp account was given by Commissioner
Larsson, the senior UK officer. Whenever an account for the charity is
opened, approval has to be given by Commissioner Larsson.
However, Dollars 8.8m of the funds were transferred to Banque Continentale
du Luxembourg over the summer, without the knowledge of most of the
charity's senior officers.
The Belgian bank account had four signatories: Col Burn; Colonel Ivor Rich,
another officer; Mr Ford and Mr Naguib. The charity had been persuaded to
allow Mr Ford and Mr Naguib to be signatories so that the bank would give
them account information, but employees of the charity insist that they
never expected Mr Ford or Mr Naguib to be involved in transferring the
funds. Any transfers from the account required two signatures.
Also during the summer, Mr John Renshaw, the chairman of the charity's
London Advisory Board and a former deputy chairman of building group John
Laing, warned the charity not to invest funds in standby letters of credit
because he was concerned the funds would be lost.
In August, Col Rich travelled to Antwerp and discovered that the Dollars
8.8m had been moved. He then travelled to the Luxembourg office of Banque
Continentale, but only Dollars 520,000 was left in the Luxembourg account.
Commissioner Larsson had not approved the opening of this account.
The funds had been transferred to Panama and Leichtenstein. The charity says
that some of the funds were eventually invested in a dogtrack in Ayr in
Scotland, a Scottish public house and a project to build an airport next to
a Scottish village. The charity has traced Dollars 1.825m of funds invested
in such projects, but is uncertain about the whereabouts of the remaining
funds.
Police were only informed officially last week of the alleged fraud by the
Salvation Army although it is understood that some police officers had
earlier obtained information that linked involved individuals with a
separate investigation.
Fraud Squad detectives are working on the theory that officers of the
Salvation Army were innocent victims in an alleged financial swindle
orchestrated by international fraudsters.
</TEXT>
