<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Spain warns of tax on currency speculators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE governor of the Bank of Spain, Mr Luis Angel Rojo, issued a veiled
warning yesterday that measures to restrict short-term currency speculation
could be reintroduced if the peseta continued to come under pressure on the
foreign exchanges.
His remarks to the economy committee of the Madrid parliament came as the
peseta appreciated against the D-Mark following what dealers said was the
third successive day of large-scale intervention by the Bank of Spain.
'We do not want to return once more to administrative measures (against
speculators),' Mr Rojo said, 'but I must tell you that there is a thinking
under way which says that some sort of tax should be established against
short-term speculation. We have not used the measures because we hope the
situation will not become alarming.'
Last September, at the height of the currency turmoil within the exchange
rate mechanism, Spain introduced emergency measures that effectively froze
trading in the peseta. The measures caused sharp selling on the domestic
equity and debt market, and were largely lifted within two weeks.
Dealers yesterday said that the governor, by referring to a special 'tax',
could have had in mind a streamlined version of the measures which would
apply only to one- to three-day peseta swap operations.
They said money traders selling pesetas 'short' might be forced to deposit
with the Bank of Spain a sum equivalent to the day's transactions at an
interest free rate and for a period of up to a year.
The Bank of Spain was estimated by some dealers to have spent some Dollars
5bn, or just over 10 per cent of Spain's reserves, defending the peseta
since pressure built up against the currency late last week.
Late yesterday the peseta had appreciated to Pta72.04 to the D-Mark against
Tuesday's closing rate of Pta72.54.
</TEXT>
