FT  25 FEB 93 / Hungary to seek finance for projects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUNGARY is set to open up infrastructure development to western investors in
an effort to pull the economy out of recession, the new finance minister
said yesterday, writes Nicholas Denton in Budapest.
Foreign companies could finance the construction of motorways, airports,
railways and eventually mines, Mr Ivan Szabo said at a parliamentary
confirmation hearing. The finance minister's infrastructure drive will
receive an early boost from the naming in the coming days of a western-led
consortium to finance, build and operate an extension of Hungary's M1
motorway to the Austrian border.
Mr Szabo also promised to back write-offs of bad debts to allow partial
sales of Hungary's four large state-owned commercial banks. This makes life
easier for the five western investment banks which last week began advising
on the privatisation of the banking sector.
