<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equities on hold for ICI statement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK STOCK market investors were keeping well below the parapet yesterday as
they waited for ICI, London's senior blue chip company, to disclose details
of the financing involved in its demerger plan when it announces trading
figures this morning. The likelihood of a near Pounds 1bn rights issue from
ICI, even though widely predicted by analysts, was enough to keep many fund
managers away from the market yesterday.
Indeed, the Footsie Index to a large extent tracked the ICI share price,
falling smartly in early trading but then rallying in the second half of the
session. The initial fall in UK equities was sparked off by a sharp fall in
the March contract on the Footsie, while the closing rally took in some
buying support from overseas investors attracted by weakness in sterling.
Also helping London was the early strength of the New York market which was
18 Dow points ahead in UK trading hours.
The final reading put the FT-SE Index at 2,817, a net loss on the day of 1
point. At these levels - the Footsie dipped to 2,810 in early deals, the
lower end of the market's trading range appears firmly held. The chances of
a fresh move to the upper end of the range, in the 2,900 area, waits upon
ICI.
The focus turned back towards the Footsie stocks, with the pharmaceuticals
leading the market when overseas buyers appeared in the final hour of trade.
The FT-SE Mid 250 Index fell 7.2 to 3,029.9. Non-Footsie shares made up 65
per cent of the day's Seaq volume total of 592.7m. Tuesday's Seaq total of
597.8m shares was worth Pounds 1.23bn at retail level.
'We will all be amazed if ICI doesn't make a rights issue this morning,'
commented one leading dealer. However, wild rumours circulated, the most
prevailing being a suggestion that Glaxo might bid for Zeneca, the proposed
pharmaceutical and bio technology company to be formed if the ICI demerger
is carried through.
The rest of the market continued to lack direction, and it was left to
corporate developments to provide what few highlights there were. British
Aerospace, disclosing a Pounds 1.2bn loss for the year, nevertheless pleased
the market with its dividend policy. Bank shares remained easier in the wake
of the increased debt provisions announced this week by National
Westminster.
The weakness in sterling, which depressed government bond prices, was noted
cautiously in an equity market still expecting further cuts in domestic
interest rates. Some strategists, however, said that such hopes were now
being reined in to 'only half a point and not necessarily at Budget time.'
The strategy team at Smith New Court warned this week that the chances of
further big falls in short-term interest rates have diminished as signs of
economic recovery become more evident. While approving of the UK market 'in
absolute terms, Smith recommends a neutral stance.
With no further important data on the UK economy expected this week, share
prices appear dependent on weighty list of impending rights issue, in which
ICI may be the most prominent but is certainly not the only feature. Even
the Pounds 1bn issue predicted from ICI would probably be acceptable in the
market but traders will be happy to have the uncertainty taken off their
shoulders.
</TEXT>
