<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Government Bonds: Currency movements supply focus as trade
slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN exchange move-ments continued to provide a focus for activity in the
bond markets, but the pace of activity slowed slightly as investors and
dealers yesterday paused to examine the sharp recent movements in currency
and bond rates, and in some cases decided to reassess recent shifts.
GERMAN bond prices retraced some of the gains they made earlier in the week,
but dealers said the declines appeared to represent a temporary correction
rather than a shift in sentiment.
Prices shed  3/8 -point after the latest provisional inflation data for
February from several German regions showed less of a slowdown than dealers
had hoped, prompting worries that any further cuts in interest rates could
be delayed.
THE JAPANESE market continued to forge ahead, buoyed by the strength of the
yen. Comments by Mr Yosihiro Hayashi, the Japanese finance minister, that
another discount rate cut could not be ruled out helped spur enthusiasm for
the market.
The 10-year No 145 benchmark was yielding just 3.79 per cent when the
Japanese market closed yesterday, down from 3.93 per cent at Tuesday's
close.
However, analysts warned that most of the good news was already in the
market and foreign investors might start taking profits following the rally
in both the Japanese bond and currency markets. For the moment, the market
is being supported by Japanese domestic investors loath to buy Japanese
equity or property.
THE weakness of sterling yesterday undermined the gilts market, which had
been in a fairly bullish mood. The March gilt futures contract at the London
International Financial Futures &amp; Options Exchange ended at 103 1/16 , down
from 103 25/32 at Tuesday's close.
The Bank of England announced that it had finally finished selling two
tranches of gilts totalling Pounds 1.35bn, announced on February 16. The
slow sales of the issue did little to reassure traders. While the currency
remains chronically weak, foreign investors are unlikely to help absorb
future gilt issues.
US TREASURY prices ended a five-day record-setting spree to move broadly
lower yesterday afternoon as the market reacted to weak bidding at the
Treasury's Dollars 11bn five-year note auction.
In spite of a substantial drop in price, the yield on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year bond remained comfortably below the 7 per cent level
through the day. In late trading, the long bond was off  27/32 at 102 15/16
, yielding 6.887 per cent. At the short end, the two-year note was  1/8
lower to yield 3.960 per cent.
There was little reaction to news that durable goods orders fell 1.7 per
cent in January, slightly less than the 2 per cent the market had expected.
The Federal Reserve arranged Dollars 2.5bn in customer repurchase agreements
when Fed funds, the rate at which banks lend to each other, were trading at
2 15/16 per cent.
The open market intervention, which adds funds to the banking system, was
expected to counter a seasonal drop in vault cash - cash held by banks to
satisfy reserve requirements. There was no policy meaning associated with
the action. The Fed's perceived target for the rate remains 3 per cent.
Bond and note prices started to tumble after the afternoon auction, where
the five-year note had a yield of 5.23 per cent, well above the
widely-expected 5.16 per cent to 5.17 per cent level.
ITALIAN bonds outperformed most other European markets, after a difficult
couple of days, by staging a small rally when it emerged that the Christian
Democrat party will back prime minister Giuliano Amato in Thursday's
confidence vote.
</TEXT>
