</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG and China Gas, Hong Kong's monopoly gas supplier controlled by the
Lee family's Henderson Investment, yesterday announced a 20 per cent
increase in net profit to HKDollars 936m (USDollars 121m) in 1992, up from
HKDollars 779m in the previous year.
Earnings were boosted by 12 per cent growth in Towngas sales. The results
were in line with expectations, but the share price reacted favourably to
the announcement of a one-for-five bonus share issue.
There was a 7 per cent increase in gas tariffs from the start of 1993, and
Mr Lee Shau Kee, chairman, predicted an increase of 70,000 customers during
the year and double-digit sales growth.
The company's enlargement of its Tai Po plant will double capacity to more
than 11m cubic metres.
