FT  25 FEB 93 / International Company News: Rio Algom profits for year
decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RIO ALGOM, an independent copper, uranium, potash and coal producer since
Rio Tinto Zinc sold its 51 per cent control to the public last June, has
reported lower profit for 1992.
Though copper prices were favourable, potash operations improved and the
Canadian dollar was lower, uranium and metals distribution results were
lower.
Profit from continuing operations was CDollars 39.4m (USDollars 31.2m), or
85 cents a share, against CDollars 44.8m, or 97 cents, a year earlier.
Revenues were little changed at CDollars 1.03bn.
On the same basis, fourth-quarter net equalled 22 cents a share against 29
cents, on revenues of CDollars 263m against CDollars 264.5m.
Rio Algom expects to be out of uranium mining by 1996 when supply contracts
with Ontario Hydro run out; it operates only one mine at present. It is
concentrating on building long-term low cost copper reserves, says the
president, Mr Colin MacAulay.
Rio's main Canadian copper holding is 34 per cent of the big Highland Valley
mine in British Columbia. It also has a strategic interest in the big El
Condor copper-gold property, also in British Columbia. Its other principal
copper holding is the Cerro Colorado mine in Chile.
