<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / International Company News: Dell shares fall 17% as equity
offer is dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Dell Computer, the fast-growing US personal computer manufacturer,
plunged by almost 17 per cent yesterday after the company announced that it
had withdrawn a planned share offering because of 'unfavourable market
conditions'.
The offering of 4m shares had originally been timed for last December but
was put off until early March following controversy over the company's
reporting of its foreign exchange dealings.
Dell's share price had fallen from Dollars 49 1/8 at the start of this month
to Dollars 36 1/4 on Tuesday amid growing concern that the personal computer
industry's price war is set to intensify.
Explaining the pulled issue, Mr Tom Meredith, Dell's chief financial
officer, said 'with interest rates where they are and with currently low
price/earnings multiples for technology stocks, we can do better for our
shareholders by accessing other sources of capital'.
He added: 'We have a strong financial position that allows us to take our
time and pick the method for funding our growth that best fits our needs.'
Dell, a pioneer in the direct selling of computers over the telephone, tried
to reassure investors that its earnings momentum was continuing. It
predicted that its revenue growth in the fiscal year to next January would
exceed 70 per cent and would make Dell a Dollars 3.4bn to Dollars 3.7bn
turnover business. It also forecast earnings per share of Dollars 3.30 to
Dollars 3.75 for 1993-94, compared to analysts' expectation of around
Dollars 2.57 in the year to last month.
Despite this, investors remained nervous at the outlook for the personal
computer market and Dell's shares closed yesterday on the Nasdaq
over-the-counter market at Dollars 30 1/8 , down Dollars 6 1/8 .
The market was particularly unsettled by reports that Mr Daniel Benton, a
computer analyst at Goldman,Sachs, yesterday removed his 'buy'
recommendation on both Dell and its rival Compaq. Goldman had been acting as
lead underwriter for the Dell offering and had been prevented from
commenting on the company until the issue was cancelled.
The currency controversy which led to the initial delay in the offering
arose last November when a Wall Street analyst suggested Dell might have
inflated earnings through its method of accounting for foreign exchange
trading.
Dell denied this, and a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation did
not find any reason for the company to restate its earnings. However, the
SEC did require Dell to make additional disclosures about its currency
trading practices.
Dell also announced yesterday that it would release its fourth quarter
results on March 9 but it added that it did not expect any appreciable
change from the projections announced on February 1, when it forecast
revenues of Dollars 615m, slightly below analysts' expectations, but more
than double the previous year.
</TEXT>
