FT  25 FEB 93 / International Company News: Atlas Copco moves ahead 14%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ATLAS COPCO, the Swedish tool manufacturing group, saw profits after
financial items rise 14 per cent in 1992 to SKr1.03bn (Dollars 134m) from
SKr902m in 1991.
The group said it benefited from restructuring and higher interest rates
which more than offset the impact of lower sales volumes. An unchanged
dividend of SKr8 per share is proposed on a 22 per cent increase in earnings
per share to SKr16.90.
Atlas forecast unchanged earnings for the current year, but it noted that
the weak sales trend which it experienced towards the end of 1992 had
continued into 1993.
Group sales rose 7 per cent last year to SKr16bn from SKr15bn, largely
reflecting the acquisition of AEG's electrical power tool operations at the
start of the year. Operating profits after depreciation climbed 7 per cent
to SKr1.13bn.
There was increased demand for drilling equipment, but low metal prices and
large inventories depressed demand in the mining sector. In industrial
markets, European demand was generally weak, apart from Germany.
Orders received rose 4 per cent to SKr15.88bn, but adjusted for comparable
units, the level dropped 4 per cent.
The group's construction and mining technique business area turned round a
SKr53m loss in 1991 to produce a SKr157m profit last year, despite a drop in
sales to SKr4.25bn from SKr4.49bn.
</TEXT>
