<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / UK Company News: Mentor creditors pass scheme of arrangement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CREDITORS OF Mentor, the Bermuda-based reinsurer which collapsed in 1985
with gross liabilities in excess of Dollars 790m, have approved a scheme of
arrangement, which should allow them to receive payment equivalent to at
least 40 cents on the dollar.
There are almost 800 UK and US creditors of Mentor. Under the provisions of
the scheme all known and potential creditors will have until June 30 1993 to
file any and all remaining claims, with the adjudication of these claims
expected to take an additional 18 months.
Mr Charles Kempe, partner of Ernst &amp; Young, said that the scheme would
require creditors to value any remaining unreported claims on an actuarial
basis which would then be adjudicated upon by Mr Kempe and Mr Nigel
Hamilton, the joint liquidators.
'The scheme represents a pioneering attempt to finalise the liquidation
through the usage of actuarial techniques,' said Mr Kempe.
Since their appointment in 1985 the joint liquidators have increased the
available assets of the estate by some Dollars 158m, including reinsurance
recoveries of Dollars 54m and Dollars 40m in cash settlements related to
litigation against the company's shareholders, directors and auditors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mentor.
</CO>
