<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 93 / Brussels aid to help ailing industrial areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Commission intends to devote more resources to poor and
industrially declining regions, including Merseyside in the UK, and eastern
Germany.
The Commission yesterday adopted a plan to try to arrest industrial decline
as part of the Ecu141.5bn (Pounds 117bn) EC structural aid programme agreed
at December's Edinburgh summit.
The traditional industrial regions of Merseyside, Hainaut in southern
Belgium, and the eastern Lander, or states, of Germany will be entitled to
the higher levels of funding until now directed to backward regions and the
poorest member states. Highlands and Islands in Scotland qualifies for the
higher funding too.
Brussels also wants to reform the Social Fund, currently used for training
both young and long-term unemployed, in order to target part of its war
chest to industries facing structural change. The aim is to retrain workers
before they become unemployed - a move seen by some members including the UK
as a disguised industrial policy. The Social Fund was worth Ecu7.2bn out of
a total EC structural aid budget of Ecu63bn in the 1989-93 period.
The Commission is also seeking more flexibility in the criteria for
allocating aid to 'Objective 2' areas, or industrial regions in decline. The
plan is to channel money to areas in danger of developing high unemployment
because they which are vulnerable to big factory closures.
This more direct attention to industrial restructuring was largely ignored
at the Edinburgh summit, when the 12 agreed the 'Delors 2' package on EC
finances for 1994-99. When the package was put together last year, the aim
was to target funds towards industries like defence, electronics, cars and
textiles, to improve EC competitiveness.
Although the emphasis now is on preserving and creating jobs, a row over
whether this constitutes market-distorting interventionism can be expected
when the Commission's plans go to the Council of Ministers.
Minister warned over aid, Page 8
</TEXT>
